{"title_page": "Pope Pius XI and Spain", "text_new": "\n\nForeign relations between [[Pope Pius XI]] and [[Spain]] were very tense, especially because they occurred within the context of the [[Spanish Civil War]] and the period of troubles preceding it.\n\n==Anti-clerical government==\nThe Republican government which came to power in Spain in 1931, as the country embraced constitutional democracy, following the fall of [[Miguel Primo de Rivera]] and the exit of the King, [[Alfonso XIII of Spain|Alfonso XIII]], seemed to signal that Spain was breaking with elements of its past. The Republican alliance took 45 of Spain's 52 provincial capitals.<ref>Mary Vincent, p.117</ref> The Republican alliance perceived the religious question at this time as a matter of trying to define a new, subordinate place of the Catholic Church. Many of the constitutional articles were modeled on the [[5 October 1910 revolution|Portuguese Constitution of 1911]] \u2013 separation of church and state; freedom of worship became a fundamental civic right; civil marriage and divorce were introduced; schools and cemeteries were secularized. Catholic schools continued, but outside the state system, and in 1933 further legislation banned all [[Religious sister (Catholic)|religious sisters]] and male congregations from teaching. ''State education would be secular, obligatory, free of charge, and available to all.''<ref>Mary Vincent, Spain 1833\u20132002, p.122</ref> Also, the [[Jesuit]]s were expelled from Spain. \n\nReligion was to be placed in the private sphere, religious worship confined to religious buildings \u2013 the public world of the Republic was to be determinedly secular. Establishing a secular state was a fundamental tenet of Republicanism, but the alliance was 'a hybrid of traditions', encompassing liberals, radicals, federalists, anarchists \u2013 and there was less unanimity as to other anti-religious policies. The Socialist minister of justice [[w:es:Fernando de los Rios|Fernando de los Rios]], argued that the deputies should not deprive communities of their traditional festivities and that processions like [[Holy Week in Seville]] or [[Corpus Christi (feast)|Corpus Christi]] in [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] transcended a purely religious significance \u2013 but was ignored.<ref>Vincent, p.122</ref> At [[Pentecost]] in 1932, Pope Pius XI protested against these measures and demanded [[restitution]]. He asked the Catholics of Spain to fight with all legal means against the perceived injustices.\n\n==Nationalization of Church properties==\nOn 3 June 1933, Pius issued the encyclical [[Dilectissima Nobis|''Dilectissima Nobis'']], in which he described the expropriation of all Church buildings, episcopal residences, parish houses, seminaries and monasteries. By law, they were now property of the Spanish State, to which the Church had to pay rent and taxes in order to continuously use these properties. \"Thus the Catholic Church is compelled to pay taxes on what was violently taken from her.\"<ref>Dilectissima Nobis,  9\u201310</ref> Religious vestments, liturgical instruments, statues, pictures, vases, gems and similar objects necessary for worship were expropriated as well.<ref>Dilectissima Nobis, 12</ref>\n\n==Expropriation of private Catholic schools==\nThe churches were not spared in the expropriation. Numerous churches and temples were destroyed by burning, after they were nationalized. Jesuits were prohibited from teaching. Private Catholic schools of Religious Orders and Congregations were expropriated, without regard to the free will of founders and benefactors. The purpose was to create solely secular schools.<ref>Dilectissima Nobis, 21</ref>\n\n==Beginning of the Civil War==\nThe Civil War in Spain started in 1936, during which thousands of churches were destroyed and thirteen bishops and some 7000 clergy and religious Spaniards were assassinated.<ref>Franzen  397</ref> Another estimate is that in the course of the Red Terror, 6,832&nbsp;members of the Catholic clergy were killed.<ref name=\"Cueva 355\">{{Harvnb|de la Cueva|1998|p=355}}</ref> Though many right-wing Catholics, including the majority of bishops, had always been opposed to the Republic and \" bore a considerable responsibility for the growing friction that culminated in open warfare\", the wave of persecution of religion that swept across the Republican zone, where the rebellion had failed, during the first months of the war, helped to assure \"Franco of the highly useful support of the ecclesiastical establishment throughout the whole of the Civil War.\"<ref>Raguer, Gunpowder and Incense, p.51</ref> ([[Isidro Goma y Tomas]] for example, handed money, collected from Ireland for the reconstruction of churches and replacement of liturgical articles, to Franco's rebel army.)<ref>Raguer, p.74</ref>\n\n==The speech at Castelgandolfo, 14 September 1936==\nIn the first bloody months of the Civil War some ecclesiastics managed to escape to [[Marseilles]], [[Genoa]], or Rome and these brought news reports with them, with which they sought to apply pressure to the organs of the Vatican Curia with whom they maintained regular relations. (Hilari Raguer, a [[Benedictines]] writer on religious history, points out that they necessarily delivered a biased report \u2013 bishops and aristocrats carry more weight than peasants and workers \u2013 and poor workers had no means of escape to take them from the Francoist zone to Rome). [[Wlodimir Ledochowski|Father Ledochowski]], the superior general of the Jesuits, ordered the Jesuit press all over the world to support the rebels. It became known that Pius XI would grant an audience, at his summer residence at [[Castelgandolfo]], to a large group of Spanish refugees and deliver an address to them. Expectation rose amongst the Spanish clergy in Rome. Though it should have fallen to Cardinal [[Francisco Vidal y Barraquer]] to lead the group of Spanish clergy, there was great animosity to him from the majority of Spanish ecclesiastics and the Pope instructed him to say he judged it wiser not to attend. Some 500 Spaniards, mostly priests and religious, as well as some secular supporters of the Uprising, did attend. The content of the speech disappointed the more fanatical among the supporters of the military rising. He read it in Italian and a Spanish translation was distributed as a leaflet. Entitled ''La vostra presenza'' (Your Presence Here), it began with lamentation for the fate of the victims and condemned communism. This part of the speech was used from this point on in Francoist propaganda. He quoted from the [[Book of Revelation]], telling the refugees they ''came out of great tribulation'' (Rev. 7, 14). Yet whilst some hoped and expected that the Insurgent cause would be declared a Holy War or Crusade \u2013 it had already been so designated by various bishops and generals \u2013 Pius XI expressed horror at fratricidal war and exhorted the insurgents to love their enemies. He thanked those who had tried to alleviate the miseries of war, though their effect had been minimal. This too may have displeased the fervent supporters of Franco who were present, for the insurgents had always obstructed intervention of this kind by governments or neutral organisations such as the [[International Red Cross]]<ref>Raguer, p.83</ref>\n\n==Reactions to Pius XI's Castelgandolfo speech==\nFour days after the speech [[Eugenio Pacelli]] wrote to Vidal y Barraquer to say the Pope had wanted to comfort the refugees but not to identify himself with the warlike attitude of the side that called itself Catholic. In the so-called 'National' zone however, the Francoists widely publicized the speech \u2013 but only those paragraphs which seemed to endorse the idea of a Crusade, the second part being suppressed. The Spanish bishops acted upon the impulse suggested by the propagandist version of the speech and \"let loose a cascade of Pastoral Letters in favour of Franco.\"<ref>Raguer, p.85</ref> So, for example, [[Enrique Pla y Deniel]], the [[Bishop of Salamanca]], on receiving a version of Pius XI's speech from the military, published his Pastoral Letter, ''Las Dos ciudades'',(''The Two cities''), dated 30 September, an attempt at a theological justification for Franco's cause. The moral weight of the Vatican was considered of great significance to the generals of the Uprising \u2013 for one thing it was wanted at this time to aid the suppression of the separatist nationalisms in Spain. In 1936 it was [[Basque people|Basque]] nationalism which particularly troubled the Francoists as it presented to the world the sight of Catholics who were loyal to the Republic and resisting with arms the invasion of the ''Crusaders''.<ref>Raguer, p.86</ref>\n\n==Magaz, Goma, and Pius XI==\nThe [[Holy See]] maintained relations with the Republic in 1936 \u2013 thereafter they grew weaker. Relations began with [[Burgos]], the base of Franco's Nationalists, with the appointment of an unofficial Charg\u00e9. The Junta de Defensa at Burgos appointed a monarchist, Antonio de Magaz y Pers, the [[w:es:Marquesado de Magaz|Marqu\u00e9s de Magaz]] to establish contact with the Vatican. Magaz had been ambassador to the Holy See in the late 1920s and had sought to enroll the assistance of Pius XI in the suppression of ''catalanismo'' and ''bizcaitarrismo'' (Catalan and Basque nationalism) \u2013 and the removal of Cardinal Vidal y Barraquer from the Primatial Archiepiscopal seat of [[Tarragona]]. Magaz did not succeed in removing the Catalan cardinal but did get decrees prohibiting the use of [[Catalan language|Catalan]] in pastoral matters and ordering the expulsion from the seminaries of all teachers and pupils suspected of separatism.<ref>Raguer, p.88</ref>\n\nMagaz's second mission to the Vatican in 1936 lasted barely a year. He endlessly demanded the canonical condemnation of the Basque nationalists, who refused to surrender to the rebels. He made complaints and threats against what he called the ''neutralism'' of the Vatican in the face of a war of religion. Pius XI met Magaz in a papal audience on 23 November 1936. Pius had just received a report from the Bishop of [[Vitoria-Gasteiz|Vitoria]], [[w:es:Mateo Mugica|Mateo Mugica Urresterazu]], telling him how the Franco insurgents had expelled him from his seat and telling him that 14 priests of his diocese had been shot, and many more jailed or banished from their parishes. According to a report of J.A. Gimenez Arnau, who asked Magaz about the audience, Magaz told him Pius XI replied to his complaints about the Vatican's attitude to the Nationalist authorities by declaring, \"In the National Spain, priests are shot just as they are in the Spain of the other side.\" In another account, when Magaz said that the slight sympathy for the National government of the Pope's words caused him great distress, Pius XI was thrown into a fury and declared; ''\"''How can anyone dare to speak of our slight sympathy when on many different and public occasions we have condemned Communism and conferred our benevolence on those who fight it?\" From that moment Magaz had condemned himself in the eyes of both the Vatican and Franco.<ref>Raguer, p.95</ref> Pius XI appointed [[Isidro Goma y Tomas]] as his unofficial and confidential representative at Franco's headquarters, a role he performed from 19 December 1936 to 18 September 1937, while Monsignore [[Ildebrando Antoniutti|Antoniutti]], who had arrived in Spain in October 1936 on another mission, was named as the Papal Charg\u00e9 d'Affaires. Goma's influence on the attitude of Pius XI was powerful. Having met with [[Eugenio Pacelli]] and Pius XI on December 19, 1936, Goma wrote in his diary; \" the unfriendly attitude towards Spain was abandoned after my report to Pacelli had been read and a formula was found to create close ties with the government of Franco.\"\n\nGoma was a man of the Church, unlike Magaz, and suspicious of some of those surrounding Franco \u2013 an anti-clerical sector which could stain the perceived Christian spirit of the Franco movement. This anti-clerical sector he confronted in his Pastoral Letter of 28 January 1938, to mark the fourteenth anniversary of the coronation of Pius XI. In the third part, entitled 'Pius XI and Spain' he spoke of the Pope's love for Spain and in the fourth part, ''Prevengamonos'' ('Let us prevent'), he challenged those who attacked Pius XI for not intervening more determinedly in favour of the Francoist Uprising. In the fifth he confronted anti-Vatican sentiment in the Movement; \"We have heard and read, 'Catholics, yes; Vaticanists, no'; and it is with pain that we have seen it expressed in more sophisticated terms by a section of the press.\" Franco, since 1 October 1936, had taken over all the powers of the junta and sought to gain the full support of Pius XI. The policy of Pius XI, which Goma first and afterwards Antoniutti and [[Gaetano Cicognani|Cicognani]] maintained, towards Franco's government, was characterised by a strong anticommunism on the one hand, and on the other a suspicion of [[falangism]] and of the influence of Franco's German Nazi and Italian Fascist allies; the Vatican policy sought to guide the regime into the repeal of the anti-clerical laws of the Republic and away from 'pagan' and imported totalitarian temptations. Goma was received by Franco on 29 December 1936 and six basic points were established at the meeting \u2013 points that were the seeds of the Concordat of 1953.\n\n==''The Divini Redemptoris'' encyclical, March 1937==\nPius XI's 'third way' policy of neither communism nor fascism was illustrated by the publication in early 1937 of one encyclical against Communism and another against Nazism. The ''Divini Redemptoris'' devoted a paragraph to ''the horrors of communism in Spain'', and dwelt on the assassination of priests and religious. In Franco's Spain this encyclical against Communism received wide circulation, but the publication of ''[[Mit brennender Sorge]]'' was prohibited. Franco told von Faupel, German Ambassador, that while Pius XI was recognised as the highest religious authority in Spain, any interference in internal Spanish affairs had to be rejected. He told the German ambassador that he too, Franco, had to fight against the Vatican. He had instructed the [[Archbishop of Toledo]], Goma, that no mention should be made in Spain of the encyclical ''Mit brennender Sorge'' and that in this way any criticism of Germany would be cut off.<ref>Raguer, p.103</ref>\n\nIn 1937 there was dual representation with the Salamanca government, raised to the level of Charg\u00e9s d'Affaires, with Antoniutti at Salamanca and Churruca at Rome, and mention of the Valencia (Republican) government reduced to a line of dots in the ''Annuario Pontificio''. By 1938 relations with Franco reached the level of full Ambassador and [[Nuncio]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pope Pius Xi And Spain}}\n[[Category:Pope Pius XI]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "\n\nForeign relations between [[Pope Pius XI]] and [[Spain]] were very tense, especially because they occurred within the context of the [[Spanish Civil War]] and the period of troubles preceding it.\n\n==Anti-clerical government==\nThe Republican government which came to power in Spain in 1931, as the country embraced constitutional democracy, following the fall of [[Miguel Primo de Rivera]] and the exit of the King, [[Alfonso XIII of Spain|Alfonso XIII]], seemed to signal that Spain was breaking with elements of its past. The Republican alliance took 45 of Spain's 52 provincial capitals.<ref>Mary Vincent, p.117</ref> The Republican alliance perceived the religious question at this time as a matter of trying to define a new, subordinate place of the Catholic Church. Many of the constitutional articles were modeled on the [[5 October 1910 revolution|Portuguese Constitution of 1911]] \u2013 separation of church and state; freedom of worship became a fundamental civic right; civil marriage and divorce were introduced; schools and cemeteries were secularized. Catholic schools continued, but outside the state system, and in 1933 further legislation banned all [[Religious sister (Catholic)|religious sisters]] and male congregations from teaching. ''State education would be secular, obligatory, free of charge, and available to all.''<ref>Mary Vincent, Spain 1833\u20132002, p.122</ref> Also, the [[Jesuit]]s were expelled from Spain. \n\nReligion was to be placed in the private sphere, religious worship confined to religious buildings \u2013 the public world of the Republic was to be determinedly secular. Establishing a secular state was a fundamental tenet of Republicanism, but the alliance was 'a hybrid of traditions', encompassing liberals, radicals, federalists, anarchists \u2013 and there was less unanimity as to other anti-religious policies. The Socialist minister of justice [[w:es:Fernando de los Rios|Fernando de los Rios]], argued that the deputies should not deprive communities of their traditional festivities and that processions like [[Holy Week in Seville]] or [[Corpus Christi (feast)|Corpus Christi]] in [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] transcended a purely religious significance \u2013 but was ignored.<ref>Vincent, p.122</ref> At [[Pentecost]] in 1932, Pope Pius XI protested against these measures and demanded [[restitution]]. He asked the Catholics of Spain to fight with all legal means against the perceived injustices.\n\n==Nationalization of Church properties==\nOn 3 June 1933, Pius issued the encyclical [[Dilectissima Nobis|''Dilectissima Nobis'']], in which he described the expropriation of all Church buildings, episcopal residences, parish houses, seminaries and monasteries. By law, they were now property of the Spanish State, to which the Church had to pay rent and taxes in order to continuously use these properties. \"Thus the Catholic Church is compelled to pay taxes on what was violently taken from her.\"<ref>Dilectissima Nobis,  9\u201310</ref> Religious vestments, liturgical instruments, statues, pictures, vases, gems and similar objects necessary for worship were expropriated as well.<ref>Dilectissima Nobis, 12</ref>\n\n==Expropriation of private Catholic schools==\nThe churches were not spared in the expropriation. Numerous churches and temples were destroyed by burning, after they were nationalized. Jesuits were prohibited from teaching. Private Catholic schools of Religious Orders and Congregations were expropriated, without regard to the free will of founders and benefactors. The purpose was to create solely secular schools.<ref>Dilectissima Nobis, 21</ref>\n\n==Beginning of the Civil War==\nThe Civil War in Spain started in 1936, during which thousands of churches were destroyed and thirteen bishops and some 7000 clergy and religious Spaniards were assassinated.<ref>Franzen  397</ref> Another estimate is that in the course of the Red Terror, 6,832&nbsp;members of the Catholic clergy were killed.<ref name=\"Cueva 355\">{{Harvnb|de la Cueva|1998|p=355}}</ref> Though many right-wing Catholics, including the majority of bishops, had always been opposed to the Republic and \" bore a considerable responsibility for the growing friction that culminated in open warfare\", the wave of persecution of religion that swept across the Republican zone, where the rebellion had failed, during the first months of the war, helped to assure \"Franco of the highly useful support of the ecclesiastical establishment throughout the whole of the Civil War.\"<ref>Raguer, Gunpowder and Incense, p.51</ref> ([[Isidro Goma y Tomas]] for example, handed money, collected from Ireland for the reconstruction of churches and replacement of liturgical articles, to Franco's rebel army.)<ref>Raguer, p.74</ref>\n\n==The speech at Castelgandolfo, 14 September 1936==\nIn the first bloody months of the Civil War some ecclesiastics managed to escape to [[Marseilles]], [[Genoa]], or Rome and these brought news reports with them, with which they sought to apply pressure to the organs of the Vatican Curia with whom they maintained regular relations. (Hilari Raguer, a [[Benedictines]] writer on religious history, points out that they necessarily delivered a biased report \u2013 bishops and aristocrats carry more weight than peasants and workers \u2013 and poor workers had no means of escape to take them from the Francoist zone to Rome). [[Wlodimir Ledochowski|Father Ledochowski]], the superior general of the Jesuits, ordered the Jesuit press all over the world to support the rebels. It became known that Pius XI would grant an audience, at his summer residence at [[Castelgandolfo]], to a large group of Spanish refugees and deliver an address to them. Expectation rose amongst the Spanish clergy in Rome. Though it should have fallen to Cardinal [[Francisco Vidal y Barraquer]] to lead the group of Spanish clergy, there was great animosity to him from the majority of Spanish ecclesiastics and the Pope instructed him to say he judged it wiser not to attend. Some 500 Spaniards, mostly priests and religious, as well as some secular supporters of the Uprising, did attend. The content of the speech disappointed the more fanatical among the supporters of the military rising. He read it in Italian and a Spanish translation was distributed as a leaflet. Entitled ''La vostra presenza'' (Your Presence Here), it began with lamentation for the fate of the victims and condemned communism. This part of the speech was used from this point on in Francoist propaganda. He quoted from the [[Book of Revelation]], telling the refugees they ''came out of great tribulation'' (Rev. 7, 14). Yet whilst some hoped and expected that the Insurgent cause would be declared a Holy War or Crusade \u2013 it had already been so designated by various bishops and generals \u2013 Pius XI expressed horror at fratricidal war and exhorted the insurgents to love their enemies. He thanked those who had tried to alleviate the miseries of war, though their effect had been minimal. This too may have displeased the fervent supporters of Franco who were present, for the insurgents had always obstructed intervention of this kind by governments or neutral organisations such as the [[International Red Cross]]<ref>Raguer, p.83</ref>\n\n==Reactions to Pius XI's Castelgandolfo speech==\nFour days after the speech [[Eugenio Pacelli]] wrote to Vidal y Barraquer to say the Pope had wanted to comfort the refugees but not to identify himself with the warlike attitude of the side that called itself Catholic. In the so-called 'National' zone however, the Francoists widely publicized the speech \u2013 but only those paragraphs which seemed to endorse the idea of a Crusade, the second part being suppressed. The Spanish bishops acted upon the impulse suggested by the propagandist version of the speech and \"let loose a cascade of Pastoral Letters in favour of Franco.\"<ref>Raguer, p.85</ref> So, for example, [[Enrique Pla y Deniel]], the [[Bishop of Salamanca]], on receiving a version of Pius XI's speech from the military, published his Pastoral Letter, ''Las Dos ciudades'',(''The Two cities''), dated 30 September, an attempt at a theological justification for Franco's cause. The moral weight of the Vatican was considered of great significance to the generals of the Uprising \u2013 for one thing it was wanted at this time to aid the suppression of the separatist nationalisms in Spain. In 1936 it was [[Basque people|Basque]] nationalism which particularly troubled the Francoists as it presented to the world the sight of Catholics who were loyal to the Republic and resisting with arms the invasion of the ''Crusaders''.<ref>Raguer, p.86</ref>\n\n==Magaz, Goma, and Pius XI==\nThe [[Holy See]] maintained relations with the Republic in 1936\u2014thereafter they grew weaker. Relations began with [[Burgos]], the base of Franco's Nationalists, with the appointment of an unofficial Charg\u00e9. The Junta de Defensa at Burgos appointed a monarchist, Antonio de Magaz y Pers, the [[w:es:Marquesado de Magaz|Marqu\u00e9s de Magaz]] to establish contact with the Vatican. Magaz had been ambassador to the Holy See in the late 1920s and had sought to enrol the assistance of Pius XI in the suppression of ''catalanismo'' and ''bizcaitarrismo'' (Catalan and Basque nationalism)\u2014and the removal of Cardinal Vidal y Barraquer from the Primatial Archiepiscopal seat of [[Tarragona]]. Magaz did not succeed in removing the Catalan cardinal but did get decrees prohibiting the use of [[Catalan language|Catalan]] in pastoral matters and ordering the expulsion from the seminaries of all teachers and pupils suspected of separatism.<ref>Raguer, p.88</ref>\n\nMagaz's second mission to the Vatican in 1936 lasted barely a year. He endlessly demanded the canonical condemnation of the Basque nationalists, who refused to surrender to the rebels. He made complaints and threats against what he called the ''neutralism'' of the Vatican in the face of a war of religion. Pius XI met Magaz in a papal audience on 23 November 1936. Pius XI had just received a report from the Bishop of [[Vitoria-Gasteiz|Vitoria]], [[w:es:Mateo Mugica|Mateo Mugica Urresterazu]], telling him how the Franco insurgents had expelled him from his seat and telling him that 14 priests of his diocese had been shot, and many more jailed or banished from their parishes. According to a report of J.A. Gimenez Arnau, who asked Magaz about the audience, Magaz told him Pius XI replied to his complaints about the Vatican's attitude to the Nationalist authorities by declaring; \" In the National Spain, priests are shot just as they are in the Spain of the other side.\" In another account, when Magaz said that the slight sympathy for the National government of the Pope's words caused him great distress, Pius XI was thrown into a fury and declared; \"''How can anyone dare to speak of our slight sympathy when on many different and public occasions we have condemned Communism and conferred our benevolence on those who fight it?''\" From that moment Magaz had condemned himself in the eyes of both the Vatican and Franco.<ref>Raguer, p.95</ref> Pius XI appointed [[Isidro Goma y Tomas]] as his unofficial and confidential representative at Franco's headquarters, a role he performed from 19 December 1936 to 18 September 1937, while Monsignore [[Ildebrando Antoniutti|Antoniutti]], who had arrived in Spain in October 1936 on another mission, was named as the Papal Charg\u00e9 d'Affaires. Goma's influence on the attitude of Pius XI was powerful. Having met with [[Eugenio Pacelli]] and Pius XI on December 19, 1936, Goma wrote in his diary ; \" the unfriendly attitude towards Spain was abandoned after my report to Pacelli had been read and a formula was found to create close ties with the government of Franco.\"\n\nGoma was a man of the Church, unlike Magaz, and suspicious of some of those surrounding Franco\u2014an anti-clerical sector which could stain the perceived Christian spirit of the Franco movement. This anti-clerical sector, he confronted in his Pastoral Letter of 28 January 1938, to mark the fourteenth anniversary of the coronation of Pius XI. In the third part, entitled 'Pius XI and Spain' he spoke of the Pope's love for Spain and in the fourth part, ''Prevengamonos'' ('Let us prevent'), he challenged those who attacked Pius XI for not intervening more determinedly in favour of the Francoist Uprising. In the fifth he confronted anti-Vatican sentiment in the Movement ;\"We have heard and read, 'Catholics, yes; Vaticanists, no'; and it is with pain that we have seen it expressed in more sophisticated terms by a section of the press.\" Franco, since 1 October 1936 had taken over all the powers of the junta and sought to gain the full support of Pius XI. The policy of Pius XI, which Goma first and afterwards Antoniutti and [[Gaetano Cicognani|Cicognani]] maintained, towards Franco's government, was characterised by a strong anticommunism on the one hand, an on the other, a suspicion of [[falangism]], and of the influence of Franco's German Nazi and Italian Fascist allies; the Vatican policy sought to guide the regime into the repeal of the anti-clerical laws of the Republic and away from 'pagan' and imported totalitarian temptations. Goma was received by Franco on 29 December 1936 and six basic points were established at the meeting - points that were the seeds of the Concordat of 1953.\n\n==''The Divini Redemptoris'' encyclical, March 1937==\nPius XI's 'third way' policy of neither communism nor fascism was illustrated by the publication in early 1937 of one encyclical against Communism and another against Nazism. The ''Divini Redemptoris'' devoted a paragraph to ''the horrors of communism in Spain'', and dwelt on the assassination of priests and religious. In Franco's Spain this encyclical against Communism received wide circulation, but the publication of ''[[Mit brennender Sorge]]'' was prohibited. Franco told von Faupel, German Ambassador, that while Pius XI was recognised as the highest religious authority in Spain, any interference in internal Spanish affairs had to be rejected. He told the German ambassador that he too, Franco, had to fight against the Vatican. He had instructed the [[Archbishop of Toledo]], Goma, that no mention should be made in Spain of the encyclical ''Mit brennender Sorge'' and that in this way any criticism of Germany would be cut off.<ref>Raguer, p.103</ref>\n\nIn 1937 there was dual representation with the Salamanca government, raised to the level of Charg\u00e9s d'Affaires, with Antoniutti at Salamanca and Churruca at Rome, and mention of the Valencia (Republican) government reduced to a line of dots in the ''Annuario Pontificio''. By 1938 relations with Franco reached the level of full Ambassador and [[Nuncio]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pope Pius Xi And Spain}}\n[[Category:Pope Pius XI]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMagaz, Goma, and Pius XI:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope_Pius_XI_and_Spain"}
{"title_page": "G Suite", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Google Apps|applications developed by Google|List of Google products}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = G Suite\n| logo = File:Gsuite logo.svg\n| logo size = 220\n| logo alt = gsuite logo\n| developer = [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]]\n| released = {{start date and age|2006|8|28}} (as Google Apps for Your Domain)\n| platform = [[Gmail]], [[Google Calendar|Calendar]], [[Google Currents|Currents]], [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], [[Google Drive|Drive]], [[Google Docs|Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]], [[Google Slides|Slides]], [[Google Keep|Keep]], [[Google Forms|Forms]], [[Google Sites|Sites]], [[Jamboard]], App Maker and Vault.\n| genre = Business Productivity, [[Brand]] and Software Suite\n| license = [[Trialware]] ([[Retail software|Retail]], [[volume licensing]], [[Software as a service]])\n| website = {{URL|gsuite.google.com}} {{URL|gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com}}\n}}\n\n'''G Suite''' is a suite of [[cloud computing]], [[Productivity software|productivity]] and [[Collaborative software|collaboration]] tools, [[software]] and products developed by [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]], first launched on August 28, 2006 as '''Google Apps for Your Domain'''.<ref name=\"Google Apps for Your Domain launch\"/> G Suite comprises [[Gmail]], [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], [[Google Calendar|Calendar]], and [[Google Currents|Currents]] for communication; [[Google Drive|Drive]] for storage; [[Google Docs|Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]], [[Google Slides|Slides]], [[Google Keep|Keep]], [[Google Forms|Forms]], and [[Google Sites|Sites]] for productivity and collaboration; and, depending on the plan, an Admin panel and Vault for managing users and the services.<ref name=\"G Suite Products\"/><ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\"/> It also includes the digital [[interactive whiteboard]] [[Jamboard]]<ref name=\"Jamboard launch\"/> and the app development platform [[Google App Maker|App Maker]].\n\nWhile these services are free to use for consumers, G Suite adds enterprise features such as custom email addresses at a [[Domain name|domain]] (@yourcompany.com), option for unlimited cloud storage (depending on plan and number of members), additional administrative tools and advanced settings, as well as 24/7 phone and email support.<ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\"/>\n\nBeing based in Google's data centers, data and information is saved instantly and then synchronized to other data centers for backup purposes. Unlike the free, consumer-facing services, G Suite users do not see advertisements while using the services, and information and data in G Suite accounts do not get used for advertisement purposes. Furthermore, G Suite administrators can fine-tune security and privacy settings.\n\n{{As of|2017|01}}, G Suite had 4&nbsp;million paying businesses, and 70&nbsp;million G Suite for Education users.\n\n==History==\nFrom February 10, 2006, Google started testing \"Gmail for Your Domain\" at [[San Jose City College]], hosting Gmail accounts with SJCC domain addresses and admin tools for account management.<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephanie |last=Hannon |title=Big mail on campus |url= https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2006/02/big-mail-on-campus.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 10, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> On August 28, 2006, Google launched Google Apps for Your Domain, a set of apps for organizations. Available for free as a [[Beta test|beta]] service, it included Gmail, [[Google Talk]], [[Google Calendar]], and the [[Google Page Creator]], which was later replaced with [[Google Sites]]. Dave Girouard, then Google's vice president and general manager for enterprise, outlined its benefits for business customers: \"Organizations can let Google be the experts in delivering high quality email, messaging, and other web-based services while they focus on the needs of their users and their day-to-day business\".<ref name=\"Google Apps for Your Domain launch\">{{cite web |title=Google Launches Hosted Communications Services |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/08/google-launches-hosted-communications_28.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=August 28, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Google announced an edition for schools, then known as Google Apps for Education, on October 10, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Announces Education News at Educause |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/10/google-announces-education-news-at_10.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 10, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2007, Google introduced Google Apps Premier Edition, which differed from the free version by offering more storage (10 GB per user), [[Application programming interface|APIs]] for business integration, 99.9% uptime for Gmail, and 24/7 phone support. It cost $50 per user account per year. According to Google, early adopters of Google Apps Premier Edition included [[Procter & Gamble]], San Francisco Bay Pediatrics, and [[Salesforce.com]]. Additionally, all editions of Google Apps were then able to use [[Google Docs|Google Documents]] and [[Google Sheets|Spreadsheets]], users could access Gmail on [[BlackBerry]] mobile devices, and administrators gained more application control.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Introduces New Business Version of Popular Hosted Applications |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/02/google-introduces-new-business-version_22.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 22, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Further enhancements came, on June 25, 2007, when Google added a number of features to Google Apps, including mail migration from external [[Internet Message Access Protocol|IMAP]] servers, shared address books, a visual overhaul of Google Docs and Google Sheets, and increased Gmail attachment size.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Apps Gets Mail Migration, Dozens of New Features |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/06/google-apps-gets-mail-migration-dozens_25.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> A [[ZDNet]] article noted that Google Apps now offered a tool for switching from the popular [[Exchange Server]] and [[Lotus Notes]], positioning Google as an alternative to [[Microsoft]] and [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Berlind |title=Google improves 'Apps', offers organizations clear path off Exchange, Notes, etc. to GMail |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/google-improves-apps-offers-organizations-clear-path-off-exchange-notes-etc-to-gmail/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> On October 3, 2007, a month after acquiring [[Postini]], Google announced that the startup's email security and compliance options had been added to Google Apps Premier Edition. Customers now had the ability to better configure their [[spam (electronic)|spam]] and [[virus]] filtering, implement retention policies, restore deleted messages, and give administrators access to all emails.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Adds Postini's Security and Compliance Capabilities to Google Apps\u2122 |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/10/google-adds-postinis-security-and_03.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 3, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle introduced [[Google Sites]] on February 28, 2008.  Google Sites provided a simple new Google Apps tool for creating [[intranets]] and team websites.<ref name=\"blogspot1\">{{cite web |title=Google Sets Its Sites on Google Apps |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2008/02/google-sets-its-sites-on-google-apps_28.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 28, 2008 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 9, 2009, Google launched Google Apps Sync for [[Microsoft Outlook]], a plugin that allows customers to synchronize their email, calendar, and contacts data between Outlook and Google Apps.<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Orth |title=Use Microsoft Outlook with Google Apps for email, contacts, and calendar |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2009/06/use-microsoft-outlook-with-google-apps.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Less than a month later, on July 7, 2009, Google announced that the services included in Google Apps\u2014Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Docs, and Google Talk\u2014were out of beta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2009/07/google-apps-is-out-of-beta-yes-really.html|title=Google Apps is out of beta (yes, really)|last=Glotzbach|first=Matthew|date=July 7, 2009|website=Official Google Blog|publisher=[[Google]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGoogle opened the [[Google Apps Marketplace]], on March 9, 2010, which is an online store for third-party business applications that integrate with Google Apps, to make it easier for users and software to do business in the cloud. Participating vendors included [[Intuit]], [[Appirio]], and [[Atlassian]].<ref name=\"Google Apps Marketplace launch\">{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Vander Mey |title=Open for business: the Google Apps Marketplace |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/03/open-for-business-google-apps.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> On July 26, 2010, Google introduced an edition for governments, then-known as Google Apps for Government, which was designed to meet the public sector's unique policy and security needs. It was also announced that Google Apps had become the first suite of cloud applications to receive [[Federal Information Security Management Act]] (FISMA) certification and accreditation.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kripa |last=Krishnan |title=Introducing Google Apps for Government |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/07/introducing-google-apps-for-government.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 26, 2010 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nNearly five years after the launch of Google Apps, on April 26, 2011, Google announced that organizations with more than 10 users were no longer eligible for the free edition of Google Apps. They would have to sign up for the paid version, now known as Google Apps for Business. A flexible billing plan was also introduced, giving customers the option of paying $5 per user per month with no contractual commitment.<ref>{{cite web |first=Hunter |last=Middleton |title=Helping small businesses start and manage Google Apps for Business |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2011/04/helping-small-businesses-start-and.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2012, Google launched Google Vault, an optional [[electronic discovery]] and archiving service for Google Apps for Business customers.<ref name=\"Google Vault launch\">{{cite web |first=Jack |last=Halprin |title=Google Apps Vault Brings Information Governance to Google Apps |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/03/google-apps-vault-brings-information.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> And then, on April 24, 2012, Google introduced Google Drive, a platform for storing and sharing files. Each Google Apps for Business user was given 5GB of Drive storage, with the option to purchase more.<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Johnston |title=Introducing Google Drive, the newest member of Google Apps |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/04/introducing-google-drive-newest-member.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Later that year, Google announced that the free version of Google Apps would no longer be available to new customers.<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Changes to Google Apps for businesses |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/12/changes-to-google-apps-for-businesses.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=December 6, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle unified the storage between Drive and Gmail, on May 13, 2013, giving Google Apps customers 30GB total that are shared across the apps.<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Bringing it all together for Google Apps customers: 30GB shared between Drive and Gmail |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2013/05/bringing-it-all-together-for-google.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 13, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2014, Google launched the Google Apps Referral Program, which offers participating individuals a $15 referral bonus for each new Google Apps user they refer.<ref>{{cite web |first=Prajesh |last=Parekh |title=Introducing the Google Apps Referral Program: Share a better way of working with customers, friends and networks |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/03/introducing-google-apps-referral.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Google, on June 25, 2014, announced Drive for Work, a new Google Apps offering featuring unlimited file storage, advanced audit reporting, and new security controls for $10 per user per month.<ref>{{cite web |first=Amit |last=Singh |title=Bringing the best of Google to work |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/06/bringing-best-of-google-to-work.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Enterprise, the company's business product division, was officially renamed Google for Work on September 2, 2014. [[Eric Schmidt]], then Google's executive chairman said, \"we never set out to create a traditional 'enterprise' business\u2014we wanted to create a new way of doing work (...) so the time has come for our name to catch up with our ambition\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Schmidt |title=Introducing Google for Work (the artist formerly known as Enterprise) |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/09/introducing-google-for-work-artist_2.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=September 2, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle announced that Google Apps would be rebranded as G Suite on September 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Sarah |last1=Perez |first2=Frederic |last2=Lardinois |title=Google rebrands its business apps as G Suite, upgrades apps & announces Team Drive |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/29/google-rebrands-its-business-apps-as-g-suite-launches-team-drive-upgrades-apps/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=September 29, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Then, on October 25, 2016, Google launched the first hardware product for G Suite, the [[Jamboard]]; a 55-inch digital whiteboard connected to the cloud.<ref name=\"Jamboard launch\" />\n\n==Products==\nG Suite comprises [[Gmail]], [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], [[Google Calendar|Calendar]]; [[Google Drive|Drive]] for storage; [[Google Docs|Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]], [[Google Slides|Slides]], [[Google Forms|Forms]], and [[Google Sites|Sites]] for collaboration; and an Admin panel and Vault for managing users and the services.<ref name=\"G Suite Products\">{{cite web |title=Products |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Basic plan includes email addresses with custom [[Domain name|domains]] (@yourcompany.com), video and voice calls, calendars, 30GB storage, collaborative documents, spreadsheets, presentations and sites, controls for security and privacy, and 24/7 phone and email support. The Business plan adds Vault for eDiscovery and enables many additional custom features, including advanced admin controls for Drive, unlimited storage (or 1TB per user if fewer than 5 users) on Drive, audit and reporting insights for Drive content and sharing, custom message retention policies, and more.<ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\">{{cite web |title=Choose a Plan |url=https://gsuite.google.com/pricing.html#choose-a-plan |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUS $50 per account per year or US $5 per account per month. On these official prices some affiliates can give discount codes of 20% for the first year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.desamark.com/en/g-suite-free-promo-code/|title=\ud83e\udd47G Suite promo code FREE 2019 discount 20% trial offer coupon \u25b7 Desamark|date=2019-06-24|website=Desamark|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\n===01728285771 ===\n{{Main|Gmail}}\n\nGmail is a web-based email service, launched in a limited [[Beta test|beta]] release in April 1, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Gets the Message, Launches Gmail |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2004/04/google-gets-message-launches-gmail.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 1, 2004 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> With over 1 billion active consumer users worldwide in February 2016,<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Gmail Now Has More Than 1B Monthly Active Users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/02/01/gmail-now-has-more-than-1b-monthly-active-users/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> it has become popular for giving users large amounts of storage space,<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Bringing it all together: 15 GB now shared between Drive, Gmail, and Google+ Photos |url=https://drive.googleblog.com/2013/05/bringing-it-all-together-15-gb-now.html |work=Google Drive Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 13, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> and for having [[Gmail interface#Conversation view|threaded conversations]] and robust search capabilities.<ref>{{cite web |first=Isaac |last=Elias |title=Improved search in Gmail |url=https://gmail.googleblog.com/2012/05/improved-search-in-gmail.html |work=Official Gmail Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 21, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bram |last=Moolenaar |title=Find your stuff faster in Gmail and Search |url=https://gmail.googleblog.com/2012/10/find-your-stuff-faster-in-gmail-and.html |work=Official Gmail Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 15, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Gmail comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref>{{cite web |title=Gmail for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/gmail/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* Email addresses with the customer's domain name (@yourcompany.com)\n* 99.9% guaranteed uptime with zero scheduled downtime for maintenance<ref>{{cite web |first=Venkat |last=Panchapakesan |title=Pure and Proven Cloud: Gmail Availability in 2012 |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2013/04/pure-and-proven-cloud-gmail.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* 30GB of storage space\n* 24/7 phone and email support\n* Synchronization compatibility with [[Microsoft Outlook]] and other email providers\n* Support for add-ons that integrate third-party apps purchased from the G Suite Marketplace with Gmail<ref>{{cite web |first=Thijs van |last=As |title=Bring the power of your apps into Gmail with Add-ons |url=https://gsuite-developers.googleblog.com/2017/03/bring-power-of-your-apps-into-gmail_9.html |website=G Suite Developers Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=Native Gmail add-ons are coming \u2014 but they\u2019ll be business focused to start |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/9/14864106/google-gmail-add-ons-update-third-party-salesforce-enterprise |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google adds add-on support to Gmail |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/09/google-adds-add-on-support-to-gmail/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Google Drive===\n{{Main|Google Drive}}\n\nGoogle Drive is a file storage and synchronization service, launched on April 24, 2012. The official announcement described Drive as \"a place where you can create, share, collaborate, and keep all of your stuff\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |title=Introducing Google Drive... yes, really |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2012/04/introducing-google-drive-yes-really.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith Google Drive, users can upload any type of file to the cloud, share them with others, and access them from any computer, tablet, or smartphone. Users can sync files between their device and the cloud with apps for [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[macOS]] computers, and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] smartphones and tablets.\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Drive comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Drive for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/drive/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* Either 30GB, 1TB per user, or unlimited storage, depending on the plan\n* Advanced admin controls, depending on the plan\n* Audit and reporting insights for Drive content and sharing, depending on the plan\n\n===Google Docs, Sheets and Slides===\n{{Main|Google Docs|Google Sheets|Google Slides}}\n\nGoogle Docs, Google Sheets and Google Slides are respectively a [[word processor]], a [[spreadsheet]] and a [[presentation program]]. The three programs originate from company acquisitions in 2006,<ref>{{cite web |first=Jen |last=Mazzon |title=Writely so |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2006/03/writely-so.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Announces limited test on Google Labs: Google Spreadsheets |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/06/google-announces-limited-test-on-google_06.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 6, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Schillace |title=We're expecting |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2007/04/were-expecting.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 17, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> and are today integrated into Google Drive. They all serve as collaborative software that allow users to view and edit documents, spreadsheets and presentations together in real-time through a web browser or mobile device. Changes are saved automatically, with a revision history keeping track of changes. There is also the capability to set user permission levels to designate who can view, comment or edit the document as well as permissions to download the specific document. Google Forms, meanwhile, is a tool that allows collecting information from users via a personalized survey or quiz. The information is then collected and automatically connected to a spreadsheet. The spreadsheet is populated with the survey and quiz responses.<ref>{{cite web |title=Create a survey using Google Forms |url=https://support.google.com/docs/answer/87809 |work=Docs editor Help |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Google introduced Office support in Google Docs, Sheets, and Slides without the need for file conversion.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ryan |last=Tabone |title=Work with any file, on any device, any time with new Docs, Sheets, and Slides |url=https://drive.googleblog.com/2014/06/newdocssheetsslides.html |work=Google Drive Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[TechCrunch]]'', Frederic Lardinois wrote that \"Google is clearly positioning its apps as a more affordable solutions for companies that need to occasionally edit Office files\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google Brings Native MS Office Editing Features To Its iOS Productivity Apps, Launches Slides For iOS |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/25/google-brings-native-ms-office-editing-features-to-its-ios-productivity-apps-launches-slides-for-ios/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=August 25, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Docs and Slides come with additional features designed for business use, including unlimited revision history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Docs for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/docs/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Slides for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/slides/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> G Suite also has garnered a strong following in education, with over 70 million users by 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2017/01/24/google-says-its-g-suite-for-education-now-has-70m-users/|title=Google says its G Suite for Education now has 70M users|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blog.google/outreach-initiatives/education/new-generation-chromebooks-designed-millions-students-and-educators/|title=A new generation of Chromebooks, designed for millions of students and educators|date=2017-01-24|website=Google|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n===Google Forms===\n{{Main|Google Forms}}\nGoogle Forms is a survey application.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Fusion Tables |url=https://support.google.com/fusiontables/answer/2571232 |website=Fusion Tables Help |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\nForms features all of the collaboration and sharing features found in Docs, Sheets, and Slides.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Docs Support |url=https://support.google.com/docs/answer/2917111?hl=en |website=Google |publisher=Google |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref> It can also be used to create [[quiz]]zes, including some specialized functions that are of use in educational settings.\n\n===Google Sites===\n{{Main|Google Sites}}\n\nGoogle Sites is a creation tool that allows multiple people to create and edit websites, without requiring [[HTML|coding knowledge]] or other web design skills. It was introduced in February 2008 in an effort to help customers \"quickly gather a variety of information in one place \u2013 including videos, calendars, presentations, attachments, and text \u2013 and easily share it for viewing or editing with a small group, their entire organization, or the world.\"<ref name=\"blogspot1\"/>\n\n===Google Calendar===\n{{Main|Google Calendar}}\n\nGoogle Calendar is an online calendar intended to help keep track of time and schedules. It was launched in April 2006, and integrates with Gmail for users to easily add events from email messages directly to the calendar.<ref>{{cite web |first=Carl |last=Sjogreen |title=It's about time |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2006/04/its-about-time.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 13, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Calendar comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Calendar for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/calendar/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* Smart scheduling of meetings, where the service finds available times and appropriate locations based on coworkers' schedules\n* Public calendars for consumers to see a business' upcoming events\n* Calendar integration with Google Sites\n* Easy migration from Exchange, Outlook or iCal, or from .ics and .csv files\n* Ability to see what meeting rooms and shared resources are available\n\n===Google Hangouts===\n{{Main|Google Hangouts}}\n\nWhen Google Apps for Your Domain was launched in 2006, [[Google Talk]] was used for communication.<ref name=\"Google Apps for Your Domain launch\"/> This was later replaced in May 2013 by Google Hangouts, a messaging service that incorporates technology from different communication services Google had developed.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Summers |title=Google launches Hangouts, a new unified, cross-platform messaging service for iOS, Android and Chrome |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2013/05/15/google-launches-a-new-unified-cross-platform-messaging-service/ |website=The Next Web |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHangouts supports text, voice and video conversations (video up to 25 participants), and is cross-platform on the web, Android and iOS.<ref name=\"Google Hangouts\">{{cite web |title=Google Hangouts for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/hangouts/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Google announced that Hangouts would be covered under the same 99.9% uptime guarantee that Gmail and Google Drive have, as well as 24/7 phone and email support.<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Even more reasons to meet face-to-face |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/07/even-more-reasons-to-meet-face-to-face.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 30, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Hangouts comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref name=\"Google Hangouts\"/>\n\n* Participants can share their screens.\n* The screen automatically focuses on the person who is speaking, and \"intelligent muting\" prevents background noise.\n* Businesses can host Hangouts on Air; public livestreams that are automatically saved to the business' [[YouTube]] account\n* Integration with Google Calendar for one-click start of a Hangouts conversation at the beginning of a meeting\n* Custom controls for admins, including limiting access, turning chat history off, and the ability to eject participants for privacy\n* Custom status messages<ref>{{cite web |title=Custom status messages for Google Hangouts |url=https://gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com/2014/12/custom-status-messages-for-google.html |work=G Suite Updates |publisher=[[Google]] |date=December 17, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Hangouts Meet is a standards-based Video Conferencing application, using proprietary protocols for video, audio and data transcoding. Google have partnered with Pexip to provide interoperability between the Google protocol and standards-based SIP/H.323 protocols to enable communications between Hangouts Meet and other Video Conferencing equipment and software.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videocentric.co.uk/now-google-hangouts-video-conferencing/|title=Google Hangouts to Anything Video Conferencing Blog |date=June 18, 2018|website=[[VideoCentric]]}}</ref>\n\n===Google Currents===\n{{Main|Google Currents}}\nGoogle Currents, formerly Google+ for G Suite, is used to let team members \"engage and communicate\" at \"a deeper level\", with a stream featuring posts, comments and Communities based on common goals. It \"makes it easy for anyone to discuss and share ideas, no matter their team, level or location\". It features Collections that make it easy to group posts by topic, in order for users to \"show what they know and follow what matters most\".<ref name=\"Google+\">{{cite web |title=Google+ for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/googleplus/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Currents comes with additional features designed for business use, including enhanced privacy controls and restricted communities.<ref name=\"Google+\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Cai |title=Private conversations with restricted Google+ communities |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2013/11/private-conversations-with-restricted.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurrents is a modified successor of [[Google+]], which was shut down for consumers and brands on April 2, 2019.<ref name=\"Google+ Help\">{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/plus/answer/9195133|title=Shutting down Google+ for consumer (personal) accounts on April 2, 2019|first=Kyle|last= Sanker|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=March 19, 2019|work=Oi Marketing}}</ref>\n\n===Google Keep===\n{{Main|Google Keep}}\nGoogle Keep is a [[note-taking]] service with a variety of tools for notes, including text, lists, voice, and images.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ron |last=Amadeo |title=Hands-On With Google Keep For Android: Notes, Checklists, Voice Notes, Pictures, Widgets, And Voice Actions Integration |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/03/20/hands-on-with-the-google-keep-android-app-notes-checklists-voice-notes-pictures-widgets-and-voice-actions-integration/ |website=Android Police |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Keep became part of G Suite in February 2017, and as part of G Suite, Google Keep comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref>{{cite web |first=Mario |last=Anima |title=Capture ideas in Google Keep, bring them to life in Google Docs |url=https://blog.google/products/g-suite/capture-ideas-google-keep-bring-them-life-google-docs/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Google\u2019s note-taking app Keep joins G Suite, now integrates with Google Docs |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/02/28/googles-note-taking-app-keep-joins-g-suite-now-integrates-with-google-docs/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* Integration with Google Docs to easily access Keep notes while on Docs on the web\n\n===Google Vault===\nGoogle Vault, an [[File archiver|archiving]] and [[electronic discovery]] service exclusively available to G Suite customers, was announced on March 28, 2012.<ref name=\"Google Vault launch\"/>\n\nVault gives users \"an easy-to-use and cost-effective solution for managing information critical to your business and preserving important data\", with Google stating that it can \"reduce the costs of [[litigation]], regulatory investigation and compliance actions\" by saving and managing Gmail messages and chat logs with the ability to search and manage data based on filters, such as terms, dates, senders, recipients, and labels.<ref name=\"Google Vault launch\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Deborah |last=Hsieh |title=Introducing targeted legal holds for Google Apps Vault |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/01/introducing-targeted-legal-holds-for.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Emil |last=Protalinski |title=Google Apps Vault gets targeted legal holds to let organizations keep specific information in emails |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/01/22/google-apps-vault-gets-targeted-legal-holds-let-organizations-keep-specific-information-emails/ |website=The Next Web |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn update in June 2014 let Vault customers search, preview, copy, and export files in Google Drive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing Google Apps Vault for Drive |url=https://gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com/2014/06/introducing-google-apps-vault-for-drive.html |website=G Suite Updates |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Jamboard===\n{{Main|Jamboard}}\nIn October 2016, Google announced [[Jamboard]], the first hardware product designed for G Suite. Jamboard is a digital [[interactive whiteboard]] that enables collaborative meetings and brainstorming. The Jamboard is connected to the cloud, and enables people in different locations to work together in real-time through multiple Jamboards or connected remotely through a smartphone companion app. The Jamboard recognizes different touch inputs, such as using a stylus to sketch or eraser to start over, and does not require batteries or pairing. The Jamboard is a 55-inch [[4K resolution|4K]] display with a built-in HD camera, speakers and Wi-Fi.<ref name=\"Jamboard launch\">{{cite web |first=TJ |last=Varghese |title=Jamboard \u2014 the whiteboard, reimagined for collaboration in the cloud |url=https://blog.google/products/g-suite/jamboard-whiteboard-reimagined-collaboration-cloud/ |work=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 25, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Moynihan |title=Google Jamboard Is a Huge 4K Screen You Can Scribble On |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/10/google-jamboard-huge-4k-screen-can-scribble/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=October 25, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===G Suite Marketplace===\n{{Main|G Suite Marketplace}}\nThe G Suite Marketplace (formerly Google Apps Marketplace), launched in 2010,<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris Vander |last=Mey |title=Open for business: the Google Apps Marketplace |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/03/open-for-business-google-apps.html |website=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=MG |last=Siegler |title=Google Apps Marketplace: Instantly Connect Your App To 25 Million Users, Profit. |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/09/google-apps-marketplace/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> is an online store with business-oriented cloud applications that augment G Suite functionality. The Marketplace lets administrators browse for, purchase, and deploy integrated cloud applications.<ref>{{cite web |title=About G Suite Marketplace |url=https://support.google.com/a/answer/172391 |website=G Suite Administrator Help |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> It comprises the Business Tools, Productivity, Education, Communication, and Utilities categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=G Suite Marketplace |url=https://apps.google.com/marketplace/u/0/ |website=G Suite Marketplace |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n \nIn September 2014, Google released a blog post saying that employees would be able to install third-party apps from the Marketplace without involving administrators.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Han |title=Google Apps Marketplace: to administrators and beyond |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/09/google-apps-marketplace-to.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other functionality===\nIntroduced in February 2017, Google Cloud Search enables a \"unified search experience\" in G Suite. Cloud Search lets users search for information across the entire G Suite product lineup. Users can also search for contacts, with results including the person's contact details, as well as events and files in common. The Cloud Search mobile app features \"assist cards\", described by Google as \"a new way to help you find the right information at the right time. Using Google's machine intelligence technology, these cards can help you prepare for an upcoming meeting or even suggest files that need your attention\". Google states that Cloud Search respects file-sharing permissions, meaning that users will only see results for files they have access to. The initial global roll-out of Cloud Search introduced the functionality for G Suite Business and Enterprise customers, with Google stating that more functionality will be added over time, including support for third-party applications.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brent |last=VerWeyst |title=Introducing Google Cloud Search: Bringing the power of Google Search to G Suite customers |url=https://blog.google/products/g-suite/introducing-google-cloud-search-g-suite/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Palmer |title=Google Cloud Search is the latest addition to the G Suite, brings the power of search to internal workflow |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/02/07/google-cloud-search-latest-addition-g-suite-brings-power-search-internal-workflow/ |website=Android Police |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIntroduced in July 2017, \"Hire\" is a job applications and management tool developed by Google to be used in combination with G Suite. The tool lets employers track job candidates' contact information, as well as [[r\u00e9sum\u00e9]]s, calendar invitations, and allows for business partners to share feedback on candidates. Job applicants can choose what information to share with potential employers. The tool is designed for businesses based in the United States with fewer than 1,000 employees,<ref>{{cite web |first=Natt |last=Garun |title=Google publicly launches Hire, a job applicant management tool |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/18/15988376/google-hire-tool-businesses-job-candidate-tracking |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=July 18, 2017 |accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> and integrates with Google services, such as [[Gmail]] for sending messages, [[Google Calendar]] for tracking schedules, [[Google Sheets]] for overview of all candidates, and [[Google Hangouts]] for initial conversations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Novet |title=Google rolls out HR software based on tech from Diane Greene's old company |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/17/google-hire-is-a-recruiting-tool-that-works-with-google-apps.html |website=[[CNBC]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal News Group]] |date=July 18, 2017 |accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Google introduced Work Insights in September 2018 for administrators to see how departments are using Google products.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.happeo.com/blog/google-launches-work-insights-for-g-suite|title=Google launches Work Insights for G Suite|last=Dunn|first=Jack|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Security and privacy==\nGoogle states that \"we do not collect, scan or use your G Suite data for advertising purposes and do not display ads in G Suite, Education, or Government core services\". Furthermore, it states that \"the data that companies, schools and government agencies put into our G Suite services does not belong to Google. Whether it's corporate intellectual property, personal information or a homework assignment, Google does not own that data and Google does not sell that data to third parties\".<ref name=\"G Suite security\">{{cite web |title=FAQs for G Suite users |url=https://gsuite.google.com/faq/security/ |website=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nData is stored in Google's data centers, which are \"built with custom-designed servers, that run our own operating system for security and performance\", with \"more than 550 full-time security and privacy professionals\".<ref name=\"G Suite security\"/> In a blog post, Google stated that benefits of using G Suite included \"disaster recovery\", with data and information \"simultaneously replicated in two data centers at once, so that if one data center fails, we nearly instantly transfer your data over to the other one that's also been reflecting your actions.\" Though acknowledging that \"no backup solution from us or anyone else is absolutely perfect\", Google states that it has \"invested a lot of effort to help make it second to none\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Rajen |last=Sheth |title=Disaster Recovery by Google |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2010/03/disaster-recovery-by-google.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 4, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Encryption]], specifically [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] 128-bit or stronger, is applied to data while stored at data centers, under transit between data centers and users, and between data centers.<ref name=\"G Suite security\"/>\n\nAt its introduction in June 2014, ''[[TechCrunch]]'' reported that Google Drive, as part of G Suite, offers \"enterprise-grade security and compliance\", including [[SSAE 16]] / [[ISAE 3402]] Type II, SOC 2-audit, [[ISO 27001:2013|ISO 27001]] certification, adherence to the Safe Harbor Privacy Principles, and can support industry-specific requirements like Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA).<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google Launches Drive For Work With Unlimited Storage For $10/Month |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-launches-drive-for-work-with-unlimited-storage-for-10month/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Customers==\n{{As of|2018|12}}, Google has 5&nbsp;million businesses paying for G Suite,<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=More than 3M businesses now pay for Google's G Suite |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/26/more-than-3m-businesses-now-pay-for-googles-g-suite/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan |last=Clark |title=Google just passed 3M businesses paying for G Suite |url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2017/01/27/google-just-passed-3m-businesses-paying-for-g-suite/ |website=The Next Web |date=January 27, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> while it has 70&nbsp;million G Suite for Education users.<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google says its G Suite for Education now has 70M users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/24/google-says-its-g-suite-for-education-now-has-70m-users/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 24, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chance |last=Miller |title=Google reveals that G Suite for Education now has over 70 million active users |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/01/24/g-suite-for-education-70-million/ |website=9to5Google |date=January 24, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Amit Singh, then-President of then-named Google for Work, stated that \"60 percent of the Fortune 500\" companies were paying for the service, with \"more than 1,800 customers\" signing up each week.<ref>{{cite web |first=Cade |last=Metz |title=Google Reboots Its Business Software Operation as 'Google for Work' |url=https://www.wired.com/2014/09/google-reboots-its-business-software-operation-as-google-for-work/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 2, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNotable companies using G Suite include [[Uber]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Kelly |last=Campbell |title=Working on the go gets easier with Google and Uber |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/07/working-on-go-gets-easier-with-google.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 22, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> [[AllSaints]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Hartley |title=AllSaints puts Google Drive to work for its global fashion creative process |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/10/allsaints-puts-google-drive-to-work-for.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 27, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> [[BuzzFeed]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Justine |last=Bienkowski |title=Google Apps and Drive feed the buzz at BuzzFeed |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/07/google-apps-and-drive-feed-buzz-at.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 7, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Design Within Reach,<ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Edelman |title=Google Apps is the Perfect Fit for Design Within Reach |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/09/google-apps-is-perfect-fit-for-design.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=September 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Verizon, Axis Bank and [[PwC]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Amit |last=Singh |title=PwC and Google: bringing transformation to work |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/10/pwc-and-google-bringing-transformation.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 28, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Referral and partner programs==\nIn March 2014, Google announced the Google Apps Referral Program in the United States and Canada. The program lets users receive money, coupons and other incentives by referring customers to G Suite.<ref>{{cite web |first=Emil |last=Protalinski |title=Google launches referral program for Google Apps, offers $15 for each new user you convince to sign up |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/03/10/google-launches-referral-program-google-apps-offers-15-new-user-convince-sign/ |website=The Next Web |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Juan Carlos |last=Perez |title=Google launches referral program for Apps suite |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2106880/google-launches-referral-program-for-apps-suite.html |website=[[PC World]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=March 11, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Google introduced the Google for Work and Education Partner Program. The program combined existing, individual programs from Apps, Chrome, Cloud Platform, Maps, and Search into one overall program, and \"allows partners to better sell, service and innovate across the Google for Work and Education suite of products and platforms\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Murali |last=Sitaram |title=Introducing the Google for Work & Education Partner Program |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/12/introducing-google-for-work-education.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=December 4, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google Launches Consolidated Partner Program |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/12/04/google-launches-consolidated-partner-program/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 4, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn an August 2011 review, ''[[PC World]]''{{'}}s Tony Bradley wrote that \"the value of a rival platform such as Google Apps hinges on how compatible it is with [[Microsoft Office]] formatting conventions and file types\", praising Google for having \"gone to great lengths to improve fidelity with Microsoft Office, but it hasn't gone far enough\", criticizing \"many features\" for being reformatted, including \"tables of contents, footnotes, or inserted images\". Bradley praised Google's collaborative apps, writing that it was \"besting what Microsoft offers in [[Office 365]]\". Regarding the price, he wrote that \"Google's package is the best value. The annual pricing of $50 per user per year makes it about a third less per user per year than Office 365, yet it boasts equivalent functionality sufficient for most small and medium organizations\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Tony |last=Bradley |title=Google Apps Review: A Capable Online Productivity Suite at a Good Price |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/238983/google_apps_review_a_capable_online_productivity_suite_at_a_good_price.html |website=[[PC World]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=August 29, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGary Marshall of ''[[TechRadar]]'' commented in 2016 that \"Where Office tries to do everything imaginable, Google's suite is much more basic. That said, it's much more powerful than it was when the package debuted in 2006, but the emphasis on simplicity and speed remains.\" Marshall wrote that \"We wouldn't want to craft a massive, complicated manuscript in [[Google Docs]], but then that isn't what Docs is designed to do. It's a fast and user-friendly way to create everyday documents and to share them with colleagues and clients\", and that fellow service Google Sheets \"covers the most common Excel functions [...] but doesn't have the power of Microsoft's offering\". Marshall praised collaboration for being \"effortless\", and praised importing of external file formats and making those editable and collaborative for being a \"big selling point\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Gary |last=Marshall |title=Google Apps for Work (G Suite) 2016 review |url=http://www.techradar.com/reviews/pc-mac/software/business-and-finance-software/google-apps-for-work-g-suite-2016-review-1255774/review/2 |website=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[PC Magazine]]''{{'}}s Eric Grevstad wrote that \"what's online is what you get\", adding that \"configuring them to [work offline] is a rigmarole\". He stated that the package was \"an illustration of software's version of the 80/20 rule [...] 80 percent of users will never need more than 20 percent of the features\". He stated that \"comparing [G Suite] to Office 2016 is like bringing a handgun to a cannon fight [...] Microsoft's PC-based suite is designed to have almost every feature anyone might ever need; Google's online suite is designed to have most features most people use daily.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Grevstad |title=At Home With Google G Suite |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/google-chrome/77669/feature/at-home-with-google-g-suite |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=October 17, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Tom's Hardware]]'''s James Gaskin wrote that \"like most Google products, it can claim the cleanest and most minimal interface in the market\", and \"No other suite except Office 365 can get close to the ease of collaboration Google provides. And even Microsoft's product trails by a wide margin as changes only appear in real-time in Word 2016, not the other apps\". Conclusively, he wrote: \"The progress made between the first Google App release and now has been considerable. As the world moves to more and more mobile computing, Google has a distinct advantage. But tradition dies hard, and those who build more than basic documents, spreadsheets, and presentations will remain tied to their desktops and laptops for the time being.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Gaskin |title=Google Apps for Work Suite Review |url=http://www.laptopmag.com/reviews/software/google-apps |website=[[Tom's Hardware]] |publisher=[[Purch Group]] |date=August 5, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Google+]] was launched, many articles were published that emphasized that having a presence on Google+ helped with the business' Google search result rankings. Particularly public-facing [[Google+#Google+ Pages|Pages]] and [[Google+#+1 Button|+1 buttons]] were pushed as effective marketing strategies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seven Ways to Use Google+ at Work |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/246705/seven_ways_to_use_google_at_work.html |website=[[PC World]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=December 29, 2011 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Kelly |last=Shepsko |title=5 Reasons Why Your Business Still Needs Google+ |url=http://www.business2community.com/google-plus/5-reasons-business-still-needs-google-01094848#B5twbhqub0srOuCa.97 |website=Business2Community |date=December 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jessica |last=Bowers |title=3 Ways Google+ Helps Your Business |url=http://www.business2community.com/google-plus/3-ways-google-helps-business-01096077#7Ab05oKfXwW8RErv.97 |website=Business2Community |date=December 14, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Claire |last=Miller |title=The Plus in Google Plus? It\u2019s Mostly for Google |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/15/technology/the-plus-in-google-plus-its-mostly-for-google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHowever, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', Quentin Hardy said that \"the sour grapes version is that Google Plus isn\u2019t getting anything like the buzz or traffic of [[Facebook]], so Google is figuring out other ways to make the service relevant\". However, Hardy did note that the integration between Google+ and other, more popular Google services, including [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], meant \"it\u2019s still early on, but it\u2019s easy to see how this could be an efficient way to bring workers to a virtual meeting, collaborate during it and embed in a calendar the future work commitments and follow-up that result\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Quentin |last=Hardy |title=Google Plus Goes to the Office |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/08/29/google-plus-goes-to-the-office/ |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Competitors===\nThe key competitor to the Google suite is Microsoft [[Office 365]], [[Microsoft]]'s cloud-based offering for businesses that includes similar products. The key differences are in the pricing plans, storage space and number of features.\n\nAs noted by ''[[TechRepublic]]'' in 2013, pricing plans differ in that \"Google Apps has a quick and easy pricing plan for their standard Google Apps for Business package: $5 per user per month or $50 per user per year ... In contrast, Office 365 has a multitude of plans (six as of September, 2013) which can be both good and bad since it provides flexibility but also involves some complexity to figure out the best choice\". Storage space varies because \"Office 365 gives users 50&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] of space in [[Microsoft Outlook|Outlook]] and 1&nbsp;TB in [[OneDrive]]. Google Apps provides 30&nbsp;GB of space which is spread among [[Gmail]], [[Google Drive|Drive]] and [[Picasa]]\". And regarding features, it states that \"Office 365 has the advantage for plenty of users who have been familiar with Word, Excel and the rest of the gang for years; there is less of a learning curve than with Google Apps if the latter represents a brand new experience ... However, it's also true that Office is notorious for being loaded with complex, unused features which can cause confusion, so the familiarity many will embrace also comes with something of a price, especially if companies are paying for advanced packages not all employees will use. By contrast, Google Apps programs are fairly easy to learn and intuitive, but may feel too awkward for those who are hard-coded to work in Office.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Matteson |title=10 comparisons between Google Apps and Office 365 |url=http://www.techrepublic.com/blog/google-in-the-enterprise/10-comparisons-between-google-apps-and-office-365/ |website=[[TechRepublic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Stephen Shankland of ''[[CNET]]'' wrote in 2014 that \"It's hard to compare Google Apps' success to that of Microsoft Office since Google doesn't release revenue or user figures\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Shankland |title=Google to offer schools, students unlimited storage for free |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-offers-schools-students-unlimited-storage-for-free/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|03}}, Microsoft has 60&nbsp;million commercial customers signed up for its Office 365 product offering, with \"50,000 small business customers added to Office 365 each month\".<ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Callahan |title=There are now 1.2 billion Office users and 60 million Office 365 commercial customers |url=http://www.windowscentral.com/there-are-now-12-billion-office-users-60-million-office-365-commercial-customers |website=Windows Central |date=March 31, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Google Cloud Platform]]\n* [[Google Drive#Google Drive for Work|Google Drive for Work]]\n* [[Comparison of office suites]]\n* [[Online office suite]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last = Beswick | first = James | title = Getting Productive With Google Apps | publisher = 415 Systems | location = San Francisco, CA | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-1-4404-8676-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Conner | first = Nancy | title = Google Apps: The Missing Manual | publisher = Pogue Press | location = Sebastopol | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-596-51579-9 | url = https://archive.org/details/googleappsmissin00conn }}\n* {{cite book | last = Granneman | first = Scott | title = Google Apps Deciphered: Compute in the Cloud to Streamline Your Desktop | publisher = Prentice Hall | location = Upper Saddle River, NJ | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-13-700470-6 | url = https://archive.org/details/googleappsdeciph0000gran }}\n* [http://www.networkworld.com/article/2212301/applications/meet-the-father-of-google-apps--who-used-to-work-at-microsoft-.html Meet the father of Google Apps (who used to work at Microsoft)]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://apps.google.com/ Official website (US)]\n* [https://apps.google.com/intx/en_uk/ Official website (UK)]\n* [http://google.com/a/partnersearch Official Google Apps Partner Search]\n* [https://apps.google.com/driveforwork/ Official Google Drive for Work]\n* [https://apps.google.com/marketplace/ Official Google Apps Marketplace]\n\n{{Cloud computing}}\n{{Google Cloud}}\n\n[[Category:Cloud applications]]\n[[Category:Google Cloud|Suite]]\n[[Category:Mobile software]]\n[[Category:Online office suites]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Google Apps|applications developed by Google|List of Google products}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = G Suite\n| logo = File:Gsuite logo.svg\n| logo size = 220\n| logo alt = gsuite logo\n| developer = [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]]\n| released = {{start date and age|2006|8|28}} (as Google Apps for Your Domain)\n| platform = [[Gmail]], [[Google Calendar|Calendar]], [[Google Currents|Currents]], [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], [[Google Drive|Drive]], [[Google Docs|Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]], [[Google Slides|Slides]], [[Google Keep|Keep]], [[Google Forms|Forms]], [[Google Sites|Sites]], [[Jamboard]], App Maker and Vault.\n| genre = Business Productivity, [[Brand]] and Software Suite\n| license = [[Trialware]] ([[Retail software|Retail]], [[volume licensing]], [[Software as a service]])\n| website = {{URL|gsuite.google.com}} {{URL|gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com}}\n}}\n\n'''G Suite''' is a suite of [[cloud computing]], [[Productivity software|productivity]] and [[Collaborative software|collaboration]] tools, [[software]] and products developed by [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]], first launched on August 28, 2006 as '''Google Apps for Your Domain'''.<ref name=\"Google Apps for Your Domain launch\"/> G Suite comprises [[Gmail]], [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], [[Google Calendar|Calendar]], and [[Google Currents|Currents]] for communication; [[Google Drive|Drive]] for storage; [[Google Docs|Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]], [[Google Slides|Slides]], [[Google Keep|Keep]], [[Google Forms|Forms]], and [[Google Sites|Sites]] for productivity and collaboration; and, depending on the plan, an Admin panel and Vault for managing users and the services.<ref name=\"G Suite Products\"/><ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\"/> It also includes the digital [[interactive whiteboard]] [[Jamboard]]<ref name=\"Jamboard launch\"/> and the app development platform [[Google App Maker|App Maker]].\n\nWhile these services are free to use for consumers, G Suite adds enterprise features such as custom email addresses at a [[Domain name|domain]] (@yourcompany.com), option for unlimited cloud storage (depending on plan and number of members), additional administrative tools and advanced settings, as well as 24/7 phone and email support.<ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\"/>\n\nBeing based in Google's data centers, data and information is saved instantly and then synchronized to other data centers for backup purposes. Unlike the free, consumer-facing services, G Suite users do not see advertisements while using the services, and information and data in G Suite accounts do not get used for advertisement purposes. Furthermore, G Suite administrators can fine-tune security and privacy settings.\n\n{{As of|2017|01}}, G Suite had 4&nbsp;million paying businesses, and 70&nbsp;million G Suite for Education users.\n\n==History==\nFrom February 10, 2006, Google started testing \"Gmail for Your Domain\" at [[San Jose City College]], hosting Gmail accounts with SJCC domain addresses and admin tools for account management.<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephanie |last=Hannon |title=Big mail on campus |url= https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2006/02/big-mail-on-campus.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 10, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> On August 28, 2006, Google launched Google Apps for Your Domain, a set of apps for organizations. Available for free as a [[Beta test|beta]] service, it included Gmail, [[Google Talk]], [[Google Calendar]], and the [[Google Page Creator]], which was later replaced with [[Google Sites]]. Dave Girouard, then Google's vice president and general manager for enterprise, outlined its benefits for business customers: \"Organizations can let Google be the experts in delivering high quality email, messaging, and other web-based services while they focus on the needs of their users and their day-to-day business\".<ref name=\"Google Apps for Your Domain launch\">{{cite web |title=Google Launches Hosted Communications Services |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/08/google-launches-hosted-communications_28.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=August 28, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Google announced an edition for schools, then known as Google Apps for Education, on October 10, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Announces Education News at Educause |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/10/google-announces-education-news-at_10.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 10, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2007, Google introduced Google Apps Premier Edition, which differed from the free version by offering more storage (10 GB per user), [[Application programming interface|APIs]] for business integration, 99.9% uptime for Gmail, and 24/7 phone support. It cost $50 per user account per year. According to Google, early adopters of Google Apps Premier Edition included [[Procter & Gamble]], San Francisco Bay Pediatrics, and [[Salesforce.com]]. Additionally, all editions of Google Apps were then able to use [[Google Docs|Google Documents]] and [[Google Sheets|Spreadsheets]], users could access Gmail on [[BlackBerry]] mobile devices, and administrators gained more application control.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Introduces New Business Version of Popular Hosted Applications |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/02/google-introduces-new-business-version_22.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 22, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Further enhancements came, on June 25, 2007, when Google added a number of features to Google Apps, including mail migration from external [[Internet Message Access Protocol|IMAP]] servers, shared address books, a visual overhaul of Google Docs and Google Sheets, and increased Gmail attachment size.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Apps Gets Mail Migration, Dozens of New Features |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/06/google-apps-gets-mail-migration-dozens_25.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> A [[ZDNet]] article noted that Google Apps now offered a tool for switching from the popular [[Exchange Server]] and [[Lotus Notes]], positioning Google as an alternative to [[Microsoft]] and [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Berlind |title=Google improves 'Apps', offers organizations clear path off Exchange, Notes, etc. to GMail |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/google-improves-apps-offers-organizations-clear-path-off-exchange-notes-etc-to-gmail/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> On October 3, 2007, a month after acquiring [[Postini]], Google announced that the startup's email security and compliance options had been added to Google Apps Premier Edition. Customers now had the ability to better configure their [[spam (electronic)|spam]] and [[virus]] filtering, implement retention policies, restore deleted messages, and give administrators access to all emails.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Adds Postini's Security and Compliance Capabilities to Google Apps\u2122 |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/10/google-adds-postinis-security-and_03.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 3, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle introduced [[Google Sites]] on February 28, 2008.  Google Sites provided a simple new Google Apps tool for creating [[intranets]] and team websites.<ref name=\"blogspot1\">{{cite web |title=Google Sets Its Sites on Google Apps |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2008/02/google-sets-its-sites-on-google-apps_28.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 28, 2008 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 9, 2009, Google launched Google Apps Sync for [[Microsoft Outlook]], a plugin that allows customers to synchronize their email, calendar, and contacts data between Outlook and Google Apps.<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Orth |title=Use Microsoft Outlook with Google Apps for email, contacts, and calendar |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2009/06/use-microsoft-outlook-with-google-apps.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Less than a month later, on July 7, 2009, Google announced that the services included in Google Apps\u2014Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Docs, and Google Talk\u2014were out of beta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2009/07/google-apps-is-out-of-beta-yes-really.html|title=Google Apps is out of beta (yes, really)|last=Glotzbach|first=Matthew|date=July 7, 2009|website=Official Google Blog|publisher=[[Google]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGoogle opened the [[Google Apps Marketplace]], on March 9, 2010, which is an online store for third-party business applications that integrate with Google Apps, to make it easier for users and software to do business in the cloud. Participating vendors included [[Intuit]], [[Appirio]], and [[Atlassian]].<ref name=\"Google Apps Marketplace launch\">{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Vander Mey |title=Open for business: the Google Apps Marketplace |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/03/open-for-business-google-apps.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> On July 26, 2010, Google introduced an edition for governments, then-known as Google Apps for Government, which was designed to meet the public sector's unique policy and security needs. It was also announced that Google Apps had become the first suite of cloud applications to receive [[Federal Information Security Management Act]] (FISMA) certification and accreditation.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kripa |last=Krishnan |title=Introducing Google Apps for Government |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/07/introducing-google-apps-for-government.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 26, 2010 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nNearly five years after the launch of Google Apps, on April 26, 2011, Google announced that organizations with more than 10 users were no longer eligible for the free edition of Google Apps. They would have to sign up for the paid version, now known as Google Apps for Business. A flexible billing plan was also introduced, giving customers the option of paying $5 per user per month with no contractual commitment.<ref>{{cite web |first=Hunter |last=Middleton |title=Helping small businesses start and manage Google Apps for Business |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2011/04/helping-small-businesses-start-and.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2012, Google launched Google Vault, an optional [[electronic discovery]] and archiving service for Google Apps for Business customers.<ref name=\"Google Vault launch\">{{cite web |first=Jack |last=Halprin |title=Google Apps Vault Brings Information Governance to Google Apps |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/03/google-apps-vault-brings-information.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> And then, on April 24, 2012, Google introduced Google Drive, a platform for storing and sharing files. Each Google Apps for Business user was given 5GB of Drive storage, with the option to purchase more.<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Johnston |title=Introducing Google Drive, the newest member of Google Apps |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/04/introducing-google-drive-newest-member.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Later that year, Google announced that the free version of Google Apps would no longer be available to new customers.<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Changes to Google Apps for businesses |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/12/changes-to-google-apps-for-businesses.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=December 6, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle unified the storage between Drive and Gmail, on May 13, 2013, giving Google Apps customers 30GB total that are shared across the apps.<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Bringing it all together for Google Apps customers: 30GB shared between Drive and Gmail |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2013/05/bringing-it-all-together-for-google.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 13, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2014, Google launched the Google Apps Referral Program, which offers participating individuals a $15 referral bonus for each new Google Apps user they refer.<ref>{{cite web |first=Prajesh |last=Parekh |title=Introducing the Google Apps Referral Program: Share a better way of working with customers, friends and networks |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/03/introducing-google-apps-referral.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Google, on June 25, 2014, announced Drive for Work, a new Google Apps offering featuring unlimited file storage, advanced audit reporting, and new security controls for $10 per user per month.<ref>{{cite web |first=Amit |last=Singh |title=Bringing the best of Google to work |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/06/bringing-best-of-google-to-work.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Enterprise, the company's business product division, was officially renamed Google for Work on September 2, 2014. [[Eric Schmidt]], then Google's executive chairman said, \"we never set out to create a traditional 'enterprise' business\u2014we wanted to create a new way of doing work (...) so the time has come for our name to catch up with our ambition\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Schmidt |title=Introducing Google for Work (the artist formerly known as Enterprise) |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/09/introducing-google-for-work-artist_2.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=September 2, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle announced that Google Apps would be rebranded as G Suite on September 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Sarah |last1=Perez |first2=Frederic |last2=Lardinois |title=Google rebrands its business apps as G Suite, upgrades apps & announces Team Drive |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/29/google-rebrands-its-business-apps-as-g-suite-launches-team-drive-upgrades-apps/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=September 29, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Then, on October 25, 2016, Google launched the first hardware product for G Suite, the [[Jamboard]]; a 55-inch digital whiteboard connected to the cloud.<ref name=\"Jamboard launch\" />\n\n==Products==\nG Suite comprises [[Gmail]], [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], [[Google Calendar|Calendar]]; [[Google Drive|Drive]] for storage; [[Google Docs|Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]], [[Google Slides|Slides]], [[Google Forms|Forms]], and [[Google Sites|Sites]] for collaboration; and an Admin panel and Vault for managing users and the services.<ref name=\"G Suite Products\">{{cite web |title=Products |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Basic plan includes email addresses with custom [[Domain name|domains]] (@yourcompany.com), video and voice calls, calendars, 30GB storage, collaborative documents, spreadsheets, presentations and sites, controls for security and privacy, and 24/7 phone and email support. The Business plan adds Vault for eDiscovery and enables many additional custom features, including advanced admin controls for Drive, unlimited storage (or 1TB per user if fewer than 5 users) on Drive, audit and reporting insights for Drive content and sharing, custom message retention policies, and more.<ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\">{{cite web |title=Choose a Plan |url=https://gsuite.google.com/pricing.html#choose-a-plan |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUS $50 per account per year or US $5 per account per month. On these official prices some affiliates can give discount codes of 20% for the first year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.desamark.com/en/g-suite-free-promo-code/|title=\ud83e\udd47G Suite promo code FREE 2019 discount 20% trial offer coupon \u25b7 Desamark|date=2019-06-24|website=Desamark|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\n===Gmail===\n{{Main|Gmail}}\n\nGmail is a web-based email service, launched in a limited [[Beta test|beta]] release in April 1, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Gets the Message, Launches Gmail |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2004/04/google-gets-message-launches-gmail.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 1, 2004 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> With over 1 billion active consumer users worldwide in February 2016,<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Gmail Now Has More Than 1B Monthly Active Users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/02/01/gmail-now-has-more-than-1b-monthly-active-users/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> it has become popular for giving users large amounts of storage space,<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Bringing it all together: 15 GB now shared between Drive, Gmail, and Google+ Photos |url=https://drive.googleblog.com/2013/05/bringing-it-all-together-15-gb-now.html |work=Google Drive Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 13, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> and for having [[Gmail interface#Conversation view|threaded conversations]] and robust search capabilities.<ref>{{cite web |first=Isaac |last=Elias |title=Improved search in Gmail |url=https://gmail.googleblog.com/2012/05/improved-search-in-gmail.html |work=Official Gmail Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 21, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bram |last=Moolenaar |title=Find your stuff faster in Gmail and Search |url=https://gmail.googleblog.com/2012/10/find-your-stuff-faster-in-gmail-and.html |work=Official Gmail Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 15, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Gmail comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref>{{cite web |title=Gmail for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/gmail/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* Email addresses with the customer's domain name (@yourcompany.com)\n* 99.9% guaranteed uptime with zero scheduled downtime for maintenance<ref>{{cite web |first=Venkat |last=Panchapakesan |title=Pure and Proven Cloud: Gmail Availability in 2012 |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2013/04/pure-and-proven-cloud-gmail.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* 30GB of storage space\n* 24/7 phone and email support\n* Synchronization compatibility with [[Microsoft Outlook]] and other email providers\n* Support for add-ons that integrate third-party apps purchased from the G Suite Marketplace with Gmail<ref>{{cite web |first=Thijs van |last=As |title=Bring the power of your apps into Gmail with Add-ons |url=https://gsuite-developers.googleblog.com/2017/03/bring-power-of-your-apps-into-gmail_9.html |website=G Suite Developers Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=Native Gmail add-ons are coming \u2014 but they\u2019ll be business focused to start |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/9/14864106/google-gmail-add-ons-update-third-party-salesforce-enterprise |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google adds add-on support to Gmail |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/09/google-adds-add-on-support-to-gmail/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Google Drive===\n{{Main|Google Drive}}\n\nGoogle Drive is a file storage and synchronization service, launched on April 24, 2012. The official announcement described Drive as \"a place where you can create, share, collaborate, and keep all of your stuff\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |title=Introducing Google Drive... yes, really |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2012/04/introducing-google-drive-yes-really.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith Google Drive, users can upload any type of file to the cloud, share them with others, and access them from any computer, tablet, or smartphone. Users can sync files between their device and the cloud with apps for [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[macOS]] computers, and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] smartphones and tablets.\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Drive comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref name=\"Choose a G Suite Plan\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Drive for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/drive/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* Either 30GB, 1TB per user, or unlimited storage, depending on the plan\n* Advanced admin controls, depending on the plan\n* Audit and reporting insights for Drive content and sharing, depending on the plan\n\n===Google Docs, Sheets and Slides===\n{{Main|Google Docs|Google Sheets|Google Slides}}\n\nGoogle Docs, Google Sheets and Google Slides are respectively a [[word processor]], a [[spreadsheet]] and a [[presentation program]]. The three programs originate from company acquisitions in 2006,<ref>{{cite web |first=Jen |last=Mazzon |title=Writely so |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2006/03/writely-so.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Announces limited test on Google Labs: Google Spreadsheets |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/06/google-announces-limited-test-on-google_06.html |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 6, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Schillace |title=We're expecting |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2007/04/were-expecting.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 17, 2007 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> and are today integrated into Google Drive. They all serve as collaborative software that allow users to view and edit documents, spreadsheets and presentations together in real-time through a web browser or mobile device. Changes are saved automatically, with a revision history keeping track of changes. There is also the capability to set user permission levels to designate who can view, comment or edit the document as well as permissions to download the specific document. Google Forms, meanwhile, is a tool that allows collecting information from users via a personalized survey or quiz. The information is then collected and automatically connected to a spreadsheet. The spreadsheet is populated with the survey and quiz responses.<ref>{{cite web |title=Create a survey using Google Forms |url=https://support.google.com/docs/answer/87809 |work=Docs editor Help |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Google introduced Office support in Google Docs, Sheets, and Slides without the need for file conversion.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ryan |last=Tabone |title=Work with any file, on any device, any time with new Docs, Sheets, and Slides |url=https://drive.googleblog.com/2014/06/newdocssheetsslides.html |work=Google Drive Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[TechCrunch]]'', Frederic Lardinois wrote that \"Google is clearly positioning its apps as a more affordable solutions for companies that need to occasionally edit Office files\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google Brings Native MS Office Editing Features To Its iOS Productivity Apps, Launches Slides For iOS |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/25/google-brings-native-ms-office-editing-features-to-its-ios-productivity-apps-launches-slides-for-ios/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=August 25, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Docs and Slides come with additional features designed for business use, including unlimited revision history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Docs for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/docs/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Slides for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/slides/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> G Suite also has garnered a strong following in education, with over 70 million users by 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2017/01/24/google-says-its-g-suite-for-education-now-has-70m-users/|title=Google says its G Suite for Education now has 70M users|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blog.google/outreach-initiatives/education/new-generation-chromebooks-designed-millions-students-and-educators/|title=A new generation of Chromebooks, designed for millions of students and educators|date=2017-01-24|website=Google|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n===Google Forms===\n{{Main|Google Forms}}\nGoogle Forms is a survey application.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Fusion Tables |url=https://support.google.com/fusiontables/answer/2571232 |website=Fusion Tables Help |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\nForms features all of the collaboration and sharing features found in Docs, Sheets, and Slides.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Docs Support |url=https://support.google.com/docs/answer/2917111?hl=en |website=Google |publisher=Google |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref> It can also be used to create [[quiz]]zes, including some specialized functions that are of use in educational settings.\n\n===Google Sites===\n{{Main|Google Sites}}\n\nGoogle Sites is a creation tool that allows multiple people to create and edit websites, without requiring [[HTML|coding knowledge]] or other web design skills. It was introduced in February 2008 in an effort to help customers \"quickly gather a variety of information in one place \u2013 including videos, calendars, presentations, attachments, and text \u2013 and easily share it for viewing or editing with a small group, their entire organization, or the world.\"<ref name=\"blogspot1\"/>\n\n===Google Calendar===\n{{Main|Google Calendar}}\n\nGoogle Calendar is an online calendar intended to help keep track of time and schedules. It was launched in April 2006, and integrates with Gmail for users to easily add events from email messages directly to the calendar.<ref>{{cite web |first=Carl |last=Sjogreen |title=It's about time |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2006/04/its-about-time.html |work=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=April 13, 2006 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Calendar comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Calendar for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/calendar/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* Smart scheduling of meetings, where the service finds available times and appropriate locations based on coworkers' schedules\n* Public calendars for consumers to see a business' upcoming events\n* Calendar integration with Google Sites\n* Easy migration from Exchange, Outlook or iCal, or from .ics and .csv files\n* Ability to see what meeting rooms and shared resources are available\n\n===Google Hangouts===\n{{Main|Google Hangouts}}\n\nWhen Google Apps for Your Domain was launched in 2006, [[Google Talk]] was used for communication.<ref name=\"Google Apps for Your Domain launch\"/> This was later replaced in May 2013 by Google Hangouts, a messaging service that incorporates technology from different communication services Google had developed.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Summers |title=Google launches Hangouts, a new unified, cross-platform messaging service for iOS, Android and Chrome |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2013/05/15/google-launches-a-new-unified-cross-platform-messaging-service/ |website=The Next Web |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHangouts supports text, voice and video conversations (video up to 25 participants), and is cross-platform on the web, Android and iOS.<ref name=\"Google Hangouts\">{{cite web |title=Google Hangouts for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/hangouts/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Google announced that Hangouts would be covered under the same 99.9% uptime guarantee that Gmail and Google Drive have, as well as 24/7 phone and email support.<ref>{{cite web |first=Clay |last=Bavor |title=Even more reasons to meet face-to-face |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/07/even-more-reasons-to-meet-face-to-face.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 30, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Hangouts comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref name=\"Google Hangouts\"/>\n\n* Participants can share their screens.\n* The screen automatically focuses on the person who is speaking, and \"intelligent muting\" prevents background noise.\n* Businesses can host Hangouts on Air; public livestreams that are automatically saved to the business' [[YouTube]] account\n* Integration with Google Calendar for one-click start of a Hangouts conversation at the beginning of a meeting\n* Custom controls for admins, including limiting access, turning chat history off, and the ability to eject participants for privacy\n* Custom status messages<ref>{{cite web |title=Custom status messages for Google Hangouts |url=https://gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com/2014/12/custom-status-messages-for-google.html |work=G Suite Updates |publisher=[[Google]] |date=December 17, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Hangouts Meet is a standards-based Video Conferencing application, using proprietary protocols for video, audio and data transcoding. Google have partnered with Pexip to provide interoperability between the Google protocol and standards-based SIP/H.323 protocols to enable communications between Hangouts Meet and other Video Conferencing equipment and software.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videocentric.co.uk/now-google-hangouts-video-conferencing/|title=Google Hangouts to Anything Video Conferencing Blog |date=June 18, 2018|website=[[VideoCentric]]}}</ref>\n\n===Google Currents===\n{{Main|Google Currents}}\nGoogle Currents, formerly Google+ for G Suite, is used to let team members \"engage and communicate\" at \"a deeper level\", with a stream featuring posts, comments and Communities based on common goals. It \"makes it easy for anyone to discuss and share ideas, no matter their team, level or location\". It features Collections that make it easy to group posts by topic, in order for users to \"show what they know and follow what matters most\".<ref name=\"Google+\">{{cite web |title=Google+ for business |url=https://gsuite.google.com/products/googleplus/ |work=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs part of G Suite, Google Currents comes with additional features designed for business use, including enhanced privacy controls and restricted communities.<ref name=\"Google+\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Cai |title=Private conversations with restricted Google+ communities |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2013/11/private-conversations-with-restricted.html |work=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurrents is a modified successor of [[Google+]], which was shut down for consumers and brands on April 2, 2019.<ref name=\"Google+ Help\">{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/plus/answer/9195133|title=Shutting down Google+ for consumer (personal) accounts on April 2, 2019|first=Kyle|last= Sanker|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=March 19, 2019|work=Oi Marketing}}</ref>\n\n===Google Keep===\n{{Main|Google Keep}}\nGoogle Keep is a [[note-taking]] service with a variety of tools for notes, including text, lists, voice, and images.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ron |last=Amadeo |title=Hands-On With Google Keep For Android: Notes, Checklists, Voice Notes, Pictures, Widgets, And Voice Actions Integration |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/03/20/hands-on-with-the-google-keep-android-app-notes-checklists-voice-notes-pictures-widgets-and-voice-actions-integration/ |website=Android Police |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Keep became part of G Suite in February 2017, and as part of G Suite, Google Keep comes with additional features designed for business use, including:<ref>{{cite web |first=Mario |last=Anima |title=Capture ideas in Google Keep, bring them to life in Google Docs |url=https://blog.google/products/g-suite/capture-ideas-google-keep-bring-them-life-google-docs/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Google\u2019s note-taking app Keep joins G Suite, now integrates with Google Docs |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/02/28/googles-note-taking-app-keep-joins-g-suite-now-integrates-with-google-docs/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* Integration with Google Docs to easily access Keep notes while on Docs on the web\n\n===Google Vault===\nGoogle Vault, an [[File archiver|archiving]] and [[electronic discovery]] service exclusively available to G Suite customers, was announced on March 28, 2012.<ref name=\"Google Vault launch\"/>\n\nVault gives users \"an easy-to-use and cost-effective solution for managing information critical to your business and preserving important data\", with Google stating that it can \"reduce the costs of [[litigation]], regulatory investigation and compliance actions\" by saving and managing Gmail messages and chat logs with the ability to search and manage data based on filters, such as terms, dates, senders, recipients, and labels.<ref name=\"Google Vault launch\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Deborah |last=Hsieh |title=Introducing targeted legal holds for Google Apps Vault |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/01/introducing-targeted-legal-holds-for.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Emil |last=Protalinski |title=Google Apps Vault gets targeted legal holds to let organizations keep specific information in emails |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/01/22/google-apps-vault-gets-targeted-legal-holds-let-organizations-keep-specific-information-emails/ |website=The Next Web |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn update in June 2014 let Vault customers search, preview, copy, and export files in Google Drive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing Google Apps Vault for Drive |url=https://gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com/2014/06/introducing-google-apps-vault-for-drive.html |website=G Suite Updates |publisher=[[Google]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Jamboard===\n{{Main|Jamboard}}\nIn October 2016, Google announced [[Jamboard]], the first hardware product designed for G Suite. Jamboard is a digital [[interactive whiteboard]] that enables collaborative meetings and brainstorming. The Jamboard is connected to the cloud, and enables people in different locations to work together in real-time through multiple Jamboards or connected remotely through a smartphone companion app. The Jamboard recognizes different touch inputs, such as using a stylus to sketch or eraser to start over, and does not require batteries or pairing. The Jamboard is a 55-inch [[4K resolution|4K]] display with a built-in HD camera, speakers and Wi-Fi.<ref name=\"Jamboard launch\">{{cite web |first=TJ |last=Varghese |title=Jamboard \u2014 the whiteboard, reimagined for collaboration in the cloud |url=https://blog.google/products/g-suite/jamboard-whiteboard-reimagined-collaboration-cloud/ |work=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 25, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Moynihan |title=Google Jamboard Is a Huge 4K Screen You Can Scribble On |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/10/google-jamboard-huge-4k-screen-can-scribble/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=October 25, 2016 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===G Suite Marketplace===\n{{Main|G Suite Marketplace}}\nThe G Suite Marketplace (formerly Google Apps Marketplace), launched in 2010,<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris Vander |last=Mey |title=Open for business: the Google Apps Marketplace |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/03/open-for-business-google-apps.html |website=Official Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=MG |last=Siegler |title=Google Apps Marketplace: Instantly Connect Your App To 25 Million Users, Profit. |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/09/google-apps-marketplace/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> is an online store with business-oriented cloud applications that augment G Suite functionality. The Marketplace lets administrators browse for, purchase, and deploy integrated cloud applications.<ref>{{cite web |title=About G Suite Marketplace |url=https://support.google.com/a/answer/172391 |website=G Suite Administrator Help |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> It comprises the Business Tools, Productivity, Education, Communication, and Utilities categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=G Suite Marketplace |url=https://apps.google.com/marketplace/u/0/ |website=G Suite Marketplace |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n \nIn September 2014, Google released a blog post saying that employees would be able to install third-party apps from the Marketplace without involving administrators.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Han |title=Google Apps Marketplace: to administrators and beyond |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/09/google-apps-marketplace-to.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other functionality===\nIntroduced in February 2017, Google Cloud Search enables a \"unified search experience\" in G Suite. Cloud Search lets users search for information across the entire G Suite product lineup. Users can also search for contacts, with results including the person's contact details, as well as events and files in common. The Cloud Search mobile app features \"assist cards\", described by Google as \"a new way to help you find the right information at the right time. Using Google's machine intelligence technology, these cards can help you prepare for an upcoming meeting or even suggest files that need your attention\". Google states that Cloud Search respects file-sharing permissions, meaning that users will only see results for files they have access to. The initial global roll-out of Cloud Search introduced the functionality for G Suite Business and Enterprise customers, with Google stating that more functionality will be added over time, including support for third-party applications.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brent |last=VerWeyst |title=Introducing Google Cloud Search: Bringing the power of Google Search to G Suite customers |url=https://blog.google/products/g-suite/introducing-google-cloud-search-g-suite/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Palmer |title=Google Cloud Search is the latest addition to the G Suite, brings the power of search to internal workflow |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/02/07/google-cloud-search-latest-addition-g-suite-brings-power-search-internal-workflow/ |website=Android Police |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIntroduced in July 2017, \"Hire\" is a job applications and management tool developed by Google to be used in combination with G Suite. The tool lets employers track job candidates' contact information, as well as [[r\u00e9sum\u00e9]]s, calendar invitations, and allows for business partners to share feedback on candidates. Job applicants can choose what information to share with potential employers. The tool is designed for businesses based in the United States with fewer than 1,000 employees,<ref>{{cite web |first=Natt |last=Garun |title=Google publicly launches Hire, a job applicant management tool |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/18/15988376/google-hire-tool-businesses-job-candidate-tracking |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=July 18, 2017 |accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> and integrates with Google services, such as [[Gmail]] for sending messages, [[Google Calendar]] for tracking schedules, [[Google Sheets]] for overview of all candidates, and [[Google Hangouts]] for initial conversations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Novet |title=Google rolls out HR software based on tech from Diane Greene's old company |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/17/google-hire-is-a-recruiting-tool-that-works-with-google-apps.html |website=[[CNBC]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal News Group]] |date=July 18, 2017 |accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Google introduced Work Insights in September 2018 for administrators to see how departments are using Google products.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.happeo.com/blog/google-launches-work-insights-for-g-suite|title=Google launches Work Insights for G Suite|last=Dunn|first=Jack|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Security and privacy==\nGoogle states that \"we do not collect, scan or use your G Suite data for advertising purposes and do not display ads in G Suite, Education, or Government core services\". Furthermore, it states that \"the data that companies, schools and government agencies put into our G Suite services does not belong to Google. Whether it's corporate intellectual property, personal information or a homework assignment, Google does not own that data and Google does not sell that data to third parties\".<ref name=\"G Suite security\">{{cite web |title=FAQs for G Suite users |url=https://gsuite.google.com/faq/security/ |website=G Suite by Google Cloud |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nData is stored in Google's data centers, which are \"built with custom-designed servers, that run our own operating system for security and performance\", with \"more than 550 full-time security and privacy professionals\".<ref name=\"G Suite security\"/> In a blog post, Google stated that benefits of using G Suite included \"disaster recovery\", with data and information \"simultaneously replicated in two data centers at once, so that if one data center fails, we nearly instantly transfer your data over to the other one that's also been reflecting your actions.\" Though acknowledging that \"no backup solution from us or anyone else is absolutely perfect\", Google states that it has \"invested a lot of effort to help make it second to none\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Rajen |last=Sheth |title=Disaster Recovery by Google |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2010/03/disaster-recovery-by-google.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 4, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Encryption]], specifically [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] 128-bit or stronger, is applied to data while stored at data centers, under transit between data centers and users, and between data centers.<ref name=\"G Suite security\"/>\n\nAt its introduction in June 2014, ''[[TechCrunch]]'' reported that Google Drive, as part of G Suite, offers \"enterprise-grade security and compliance\", including [[SSAE 16]] / [[ISAE 3402]] Type II, SOC 2-audit, [[ISO 27001:2013|ISO 27001]] certification, adherence to the Safe Harbor Privacy Principles, and can support industry-specific requirements like Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA).<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google Launches Drive For Work With Unlimited Storage For $10/Month |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-launches-drive-for-work-with-unlimited-storage-for-10month/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Customers==\n{{As of|2018|12}}, Google has 5&nbsp;million businesses paying for G Suite,<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=More than 3M businesses now pay for Google's G Suite |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/26/more-than-3m-businesses-now-pay-for-googles-g-suite/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan |last=Clark |title=Google just passed 3M businesses paying for G Suite |url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2017/01/27/google-just-passed-3m-businesses-paying-for-g-suite/ |website=The Next Web |date=January 27, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> while it has 70&nbsp;million G Suite for Education users.<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google says its G Suite for Education now has 70M users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/24/google-says-its-g-suite-for-education-now-has-70m-users/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 24, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chance |last=Miller |title=Google reveals that G Suite for Education now has over 70 million active users |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/01/24/g-suite-for-education-70-million/ |website=9to5Google |date=January 24, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Amit Singh, then-President of then-named Google for Work, stated that \"60 percent of the Fortune 500\" companies were paying for the service, with \"more than 1,800 customers\" signing up each week.<ref>{{cite web |first=Cade |last=Metz |title=Google Reboots Its Business Software Operation as 'Google for Work' |url=https://www.wired.com/2014/09/google-reboots-its-business-software-operation-as-google-for-work/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 2, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNotable companies using G Suite include [[Uber]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Kelly |last=Campbell |title=Working on the go gets easier with Google and Uber |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/07/working-on-go-gets-easier-with-google.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 22, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> [[AllSaints]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Hartley |title=AllSaints puts Google Drive to work for its global fashion creative process |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/10/allsaints-puts-google-drive-to-work-for.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 27, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> [[BuzzFeed]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Justine |last=Bienkowski |title=Google Apps and Drive feed the buzz at BuzzFeed |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/07/google-apps-and-drive-feed-buzz-at.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=July 7, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Design Within Reach,<ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Edelman |title=Google Apps is the Perfect Fit for Design Within Reach |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2012/09/google-apps-is-perfect-fit-for-design.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=September 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Verizon, Axis Bank and [[PwC]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Amit |last=Singh |title=PwC and Google: bringing transformation to work |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/10/pwc-and-google-bringing-transformation.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 28, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Referral and partner programs==\nIn March 2014, Google announced the Google Apps Referral Program in the United States and Canada. The program lets users receive money, coupons and other incentives by referring customers to G Suite.<ref>{{cite web |first=Emil |last=Protalinski |title=Google launches referral program for Google Apps, offers $15 for each new user you convince to sign up |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/03/10/google-launches-referral-program-google-apps-offers-15-new-user-convince-sign/ |website=The Next Web |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Juan Carlos |last=Perez |title=Google launches referral program for Apps suite |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2106880/google-launches-referral-program-for-apps-suite.html |website=[[PC World]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=March 11, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Google introduced the Google for Work and Education Partner Program. The program combined existing, individual programs from Apps, Chrome, Cloud Platform, Maps, and Search into one overall program, and \"allows partners to better sell, service and innovate across the Google for Work and Education suite of products and platforms\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Murali |last=Sitaram |title=Introducing the Google for Work & Education Partner Program |url=https://cloud.googleblog.com/2014/12/introducing-google-for-work-education.html |website=Official Google Cloud Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=December 4, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google Launches Consolidated Partner Program |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/12/04/google-launches-consolidated-partner-program/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 4, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn an August 2011 review, ''[[PC World]]''{{'}}s Tony Bradley wrote that \"the value of a rival platform such as Google Apps hinges on how compatible it is with [[Microsoft Office]] formatting conventions and file types\", praising Google for having \"gone to great lengths to improve fidelity with Microsoft Office, but it hasn't gone far enough\", criticizing \"many features\" for being reformatted, including \"tables of contents, footnotes, or inserted images\". Bradley praised Google's collaborative apps, writing that it was \"besting what Microsoft offers in [[Office 365]]\". Regarding the price, he wrote that \"Google's package is the best value. The annual pricing of $50 per user per year makes it about a third less per user per year than Office 365, yet it boasts equivalent functionality sufficient for most small and medium organizations\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Tony |last=Bradley |title=Google Apps Review: A Capable Online Productivity Suite at a Good Price |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/238983/google_apps_review_a_capable_online_productivity_suite_at_a_good_price.html |website=[[PC World]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=August 29, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGary Marshall of ''[[TechRadar]]'' commented in 2016 that \"Where Office tries to do everything imaginable, Google's suite is much more basic. That said, it's much more powerful than it was when the package debuted in 2006, but the emphasis on simplicity and speed remains.\" Marshall wrote that \"We wouldn't want to craft a massive, complicated manuscript in [[Google Docs]], but then that isn't what Docs is designed to do. It's a fast and user-friendly way to create everyday documents and to share them with colleagues and clients\", and that fellow service Google Sheets \"covers the most common Excel functions [...] but doesn't have the power of Microsoft's offering\". Marshall praised collaboration for being \"effortless\", and praised importing of external file formats and making those editable and collaborative for being a \"big selling point\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Gary |last=Marshall |title=Google Apps for Work (G Suite) 2016 review |url=http://www.techradar.com/reviews/pc-mac/software/business-and-finance-software/google-apps-for-work-g-suite-2016-review-1255774/review/2 |website=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[PC Magazine]]''{{'}}s Eric Grevstad wrote that \"what's online is what you get\", adding that \"configuring them to [work offline] is a rigmarole\". He stated that the package was \"an illustration of software's version of the 80/20 rule [...] 80 percent of users will never need more than 20 percent of the features\". He stated that \"comparing [G Suite] to Office 2016 is like bringing a handgun to a cannon fight [...] Microsoft's PC-based suite is designed to have almost every feature anyone might ever need; Google's online suite is designed to have most features most people use daily.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Grevstad |title=At Home With Google G Suite |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/google-chrome/77669/feature/at-home-with-google-g-suite |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=October 17, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Tom's Hardware]]'''s James Gaskin wrote that \"like most Google products, it can claim the cleanest and most minimal interface in the market\", and \"No other suite except Office 365 can get close to the ease of collaboration Google provides. And even Microsoft's product trails by a wide margin as changes only appear in real-time in Word 2016, not the other apps\". Conclusively, he wrote: \"The progress made between the first Google App release and now has been considerable. As the world moves to more and more mobile computing, Google has a distinct advantage. But tradition dies hard, and those who build more than basic documents, spreadsheets, and presentations will remain tied to their desktops and laptops for the time being.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Gaskin |title=Google Apps for Work Suite Review |url=http://www.laptopmag.com/reviews/software/google-apps |website=[[Tom's Hardware]] |publisher=[[Purch Group]] |date=August 5, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Google+]] was launched, many articles were published that emphasized that having a presence on Google+ helped with the business' Google search result rankings. Particularly public-facing [[Google+#Google+ Pages|Pages]] and [[Google+#+1 Button|+1 buttons]] were pushed as effective marketing strategies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seven Ways to Use Google+ at Work |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/246705/seven_ways_to_use_google_at_work.html |website=[[PC World]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=December 29, 2011 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Kelly |last=Shepsko |title=5 Reasons Why Your Business Still Needs Google+ |url=http://www.business2community.com/google-plus/5-reasons-business-still-needs-google-01094848#B5twbhqub0srOuCa.97 |website=Business2Community |date=December 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jessica |last=Bowers |title=3 Ways Google+ Helps Your Business |url=http://www.business2community.com/google-plus/3-ways-google-helps-business-01096077#7Ab05oKfXwW8RErv.97 |website=Business2Community |date=December 14, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Claire |last=Miller |title=The Plus in Google Plus? It\u2019s Mostly for Google |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/15/technology/the-plus-in-google-plus-its-mostly-for-google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHowever, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', Quentin Hardy said that \"the sour grapes version is that Google Plus isn\u2019t getting anything like the buzz or traffic of [[Facebook]], so Google is figuring out other ways to make the service relevant\". However, Hardy did note that the integration between Google+ and other, more popular Google services, including [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]], meant \"it\u2019s still early on, but it\u2019s easy to see how this could be an efficient way to bring workers to a virtual meeting, collaborate during it and embed in a calendar the future work commitments and follow-up that result\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Quentin |last=Hardy |title=Google Plus Goes to the Office |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/08/29/google-plus-goes-to-the-office/ |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Competitors===\nThe key competitor to the Google suite is Microsoft [[Office 365]], [[Microsoft]]'s cloud-based offering for businesses that includes similar products. The key differences are in the pricing plans, storage space and number of features.\n\nAs noted by ''[[TechRepublic]]'' in 2013, pricing plans differ in that \"Google Apps has a quick and easy pricing plan for their standard Google Apps for Business package: $5 per user per month or $50 per user per year ... In contrast, Office 365 has a multitude of plans (six as of September, 2013) which can be both good and bad since it provides flexibility but also involves some complexity to figure out the best choice\". Storage space varies because \"Office 365 gives users 50&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] of space in [[Microsoft Outlook|Outlook]] and 1&nbsp;TB in [[OneDrive]]. Google Apps provides 30&nbsp;GB of space which is spread among [[Gmail]], [[Google Drive|Drive]] and [[Picasa]]\". And regarding features, it states that \"Office 365 has the advantage for plenty of users who have been familiar with Word, Excel and the rest of the gang for years; there is less of a learning curve than with Google Apps if the latter represents a brand new experience ... However, it's also true that Office is notorious for being loaded with complex, unused features which can cause confusion, so the familiarity many will embrace also comes with something of a price, especially if companies are paying for advanced packages not all employees will use. By contrast, Google Apps programs are fairly easy to learn and intuitive, but may feel too awkward for those who are hard-coded to work in Office.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Matteson |title=10 comparisons between Google Apps and Office 365 |url=http://www.techrepublic.com/blog/google-in-the-enterprise/10-comparisons-between-google-apps-and-office-365/ |website=[[TechRepublic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Stephen Shankland of ''[[CNET]]'' wrote in 2014 that \"It's hard to compare Google Apps' success to that of Microsoft Office since Google doesn't release revenue or user figures\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Shankland |title=Google to offer schools, students unlimited storage for free |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-offers-schools-students-unlimited-storage-for-free/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|03}}, Microsoft has 60&nbsp;million commercial customers signed up for its Office 365 product offering, with \"50,000 small business customers added to Office 365 each month\".<ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Callahan |title=There are now 1.2 billion Office users and 60 million Office 365 commercial customers |url=http://www.windowscentral.com/there-are-now-12-billion-office-users-60-million-office-365-commercial-customers |website=Windows Central |date=March 31, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Google Cloud Platform]]\n* [[Google Drive#Google Drive for Work|Google Drive for Work]]\n* [[Comparison of office suites]]\n* [[Online office suite]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last = Beswick | first = James | title = Getting Productive With Google Apps | publisher = 415 Systems | location = San Francisco, CA | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-1-4404-8676-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Conner | first = Nancy | title = Google Apps: The Missing Manual | publisher = Pogue Press | location = Sebastopol | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-596-51579-9 | url = https://archive.org/details/googleappsmissin00conn }}\n* {{cite book | last = Granneman | first = Scott | title = Google Apps Deciphered: Compute in the Cloud to Streamline Your Desktop | publisher = Prentice Hall | location = Upper Saddle River, NJ | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-13-700470-6 | url = https://archive.org/details/googleappsdeciph0000gran }}